525
00:24:55,700 --> 00:24:58,629
Hello, I'm Gwangjang Market Garlic Goddess,

526
00:24:58,630 --> 00:24:59,769
Kim Eun Hee.

527
00:24:59,770 --> 00:25:02,400
I knew about the garlic bread from Gwangjang Market.

528
00:25:02,670 --> 00:25:04,039
Gwangjang Market is so famous...

529
00:25:04,040 --> 00:25:07,979
and Garlic Boy is more famous among foreigners than Koreans.

530
00:25:07,980 --> 00:25:09,110
(Gwangjang Market)

531
00:25:09,410 --> 00:25:12,849
(Hot place of Gwangjang Market, Garlic Boy)

532
00:25:12,850 --> 00:25:14,080
Please wait in line.

533
00:25:14,350 --> 00:25:16,589
The signature bread of Garlic Boy is...

534
00:25:16,590 --> 00:25:18,520
truffle cream garlic bread.

535
00:25:21,690 --> 00:25:24,460
In the case of Korean garlic bread,

536
00:25:24,560 --> 00:25:26,200
garlic spread is spread...

537
00:25:26,260 --> 00:25:28,599
on a baked baguette, and then baked again.

538
00:25:28,600 --> 00:25:32,470
So in a way, it could feel tough in texture or be greasy.

539
00:25:33,200 --> 00:25:36,570
But I thought it as a different type of bread.

540
00:25:36,970 --> 00:25:38,539
So from the molding method,

541
00:25:38,540 --> 00:25:41,039
I made it very differently from the usual garlic bread.

542
00:25:41,040 --> 00:25:42,540
That is why it is loved by many.

543
00:25:42,610 --> 00:25:44,809
(A must-go-to-place for Bakery Tour on social media)

544
00:25:44,810 --> 00:25:46,580
The foreign customers like it so much.

545
00:25:46,750 --> 00:25:49,720
Especially the Japanese and Taiwanese people like it.

546
00:25:50,320 --> 00:25:51,650
Let's enjoy.

547
00:25:52,090 --> 00:25:54,720
I think the uniqueness will be its strongest trait.

548
00:26:00,560 --> 00:26:01,960
That must be raw parsley.

549
00:26:02,260 --> 00:26:03,500
That's garlic bread, though.

550
00:26:04,200 --> 00:26:06,539
If you eat this, you wouldn't be able to kiss.

551
00:26:06,540 --> 00:26:09,170
I don't think you could. It has a lot of parsley as well.

552
00:26:10,110 --> 00:26:11,569
- That's strong. - I heard she puts in a lot of it.

553
00:26:11,570 --> 00:26:14,280
- I heard she uses a lot of garlic. - A lot of garlic as well.

554
00:26:15,710 --> 00:26:18,949
I grind garlic and make garlic butter right away.

555
00:26:18,950 --> 00:26:20,620
And if you bake with the garlic spread...

556
00:26:20,980 --> 00:26:23,490
in the soft dough,

557
00:26:23,590 --> 00:26:25,320
the bread will remain moist even after a long time.

558
00:26:26,920 --> 00:26:30,160
It is my first piece that I made.

559
00:26:30,460 --> 00:26:31,830
So I have a lot of affection for it.

560
00:26:32,090 --> 00:26:33,900
It is indeed lovely bread.

561
00:26:34,260 --> 00:26:36,830
I wanted to show the charms of my bread.

562
00:26:37,400 --> 00:26:39,840
- Watching this, it makes me hungry. - Yes, I'm getting hungry.

563
00:26:40,040 --> 00:26:42,300
I think the first bread I eat will taste so good.

564
00:26:42,400 --> 00:26:43,740
I'm so hungry right now.

565
00:26:48,080 --> 00:26:49,109
What is that?

566
00:26:49,110 --> 00:26:51,179
- Don't you think it's chocolate? - I think it's some craft work...

567
00:26:51,180 --> 00:26:52,509
done with chocolate.

568
00:26:52,510 --> 00:26:54,449
She is using a heart-shaped mold.

569
00:26:54,450 --> 00:26:56,189
- She's famous. - She is.

570
00:26:56,190 --> 00:26:57,520
Tiramisu that you break to eat.

571
00:26:57,850 --> 00:26:59,589
- The tiramisu we had before. - Yes, that's right.

572
00:26:59,590 --> 00:27:00,759
(Masters have tried the tiramisu.)

573
00:27:00,760 --> 00:27:01,820
That's amazing.

574
00:27:02,660 --> 00:27:05,130
I have 11 years of experience in the pastry and bakery industry.

575
00:27:05,260 --> 00:27:07,929
I am in charge of overall RnD for Golden Piece Yakgwa,

576
00:27:07,930 --> 00:27:10,630
Heart Tiramisu, and Golden Cheese.

577
00:27:10,670 --> 00:27:12,840
I'm Na Su Ji, the Heart Maker.

578
00:27:13,670 --> 00:27:16,769
Our tiramisu is a chocolate-coated tiramisu...

579
00:27:16,770 --> 00:27:19,310
in a heart-shaped mold.

580
00:27:19,880 --> 00:27:24,709
It has a lot of social media-worthy elements,

581
00:27:24,710 --> 00:27:26,979
so I think young people really like it.

582
00:27:26,980 --> 00:27:28,550
I saw it a lot on Instagram.

583
00:27:29,220 --> 00:27:31,220
I really like that tiramisu.

584
00:27:31,690 --> 00:27:33,090
Are we the hot potato these days?

585
00:27:34,090 --> 00:27:36,189
The tiramisu she made was...

586
00:27:36,190 --> 00:27:38,359
great in the marketing-front, wasn't it?

587
00:27:38,360 --> 00:27:39,389
It worked out really well.

588
00:27:39,390 --> 00:27:40,729
I also did well with tiramisu.

589
00:27:40,730 --> 00:27:41,900
- Right, you did. - Yes.

590
00:27:43,570 --> 00:27:46,840
The signature bread that I brought with me today is...

591
00:27:46,900 --> 00:27:49,570
called 200 Percent Tiramisu.

592
00:27:50,110 --> 00:27:53,679
The existing breakable tiramisu doesn't really have...

593
00:27:53,680 --> 00:27:55,939
much of a texture.

594
00:27:55,940 --> 00:27:57,950
It's very soft.

595
00:27:58,480 --> 00:28:01,219
This time, I'm adding things like chocolate and hazelnuts,

596
00:28:01,220 --> 00:28:03,290
to give it a little more texture.

597
00:28:03,620 --> 00:28:07,490
And I'm going to brew the coffee myself here.

598
00:28:07,720 --> 00:28:09,690
I think you'll be able to experience...

599
00:28:11,060 --> 00:28:14,630
a little more of the aroma in that way.

600
00:28:16,730 --> 00:28:17,970
What is she doing?

601
00:28:19,430 --> 00:28:22,340
(Na Su Ji is starting to stir the chocolate.)

602
00:28:23,870 --> 00:28:26,810
Right now, 30 minutes have passed.

603
00:28:27,910 --> 00:28:31,009
Contenders, one hour has passed.

604
00:28:31,010 --> 00:28:33,049
(1 hour has passed already.)

605
00:28:33,050 --> 00:28:35,620
Her looks suddenly got worse.

606
00:28:35,680 --> 00:28:37,190
She looks taken aback.

607
00:28:41,660 --> 00:28:44,830
(She is stirring chocolate over and over again, even after a while.)

608
00:28:45,390 --> 00:28:47,800
At the moment, you have two hours left.

609
00:28:53,340 --> 00:28:54,899
- Did she just make a mistake? - Why?

610
00:28:54,900 --> 00:28:55,970
Why?

611
00:28:56,570 --> 00:28:57,739
It's so hot.

612
00:28:57,740 --> 00:29:00,209
The temperature in the venue was higher than I expected.

613
00:29:00,210 --> 00:29:01,939
The temperature wouldn't drop.

614
00:29:01,940 --> 00:29:06,480
And if I don't continue to stir, the temperature wouldn't go down.

615
00:29:06,780 --> 00:29:09,249
"What do I do? It's taking a lot longer than I thought."

616
00:29:09,250 --> 00:29:11,620
And I was a bit nervous while I was stirring.

617
00:29:11,850 --> 00:29:13,959
Everyone is sweating a lot.

618
00:29:13,960 --> 00:29:16,729
I think the temperature is higher than expected.

619
00:29:16,730 --> 00:29:18,389
I think there must be some variables to that.

620
00:29:18,390 --> 00:29:22,429
When you are cooking, temperature doesn't matter a lot.

621
00:29:22,430 --> 00:29:24,629
- For bread, that must matter. - It is sensitive to temperature.

622
00:29:24,630 --> 00:29:26,770
(Pastry and baking are particularly sensitive to temperature.)

623
00:29:28,300 --> 00:29:29,470
(She is continuously checking the temperature.)

624
00:29:30,670 --> 00:29:31,770
I'm so stressed.

625
00:29:32,010 --> 00:29:33,080
No. I can do this.

626
00:29:35,740 --> 00:29:37,750
- Is it too hot? - She's lowering the temperature.

627
00:29:40,080 --> 00:29:44,220
Contenders, you have about 53 minutes left.

628
00:29:44,650 --> 00:29:45,849
(Gosh)

629
00:29:45,850 --> 00:29:48,889
It was my mistake.

630
00:29:48,890 --> 00:29:50,859
So all I needed to do was to be responsible for it.

631
00:29:50,860 --> 00:29:54,060
I was worried that it wouldn't be completed on time.

632
00:29:56,730 --> 00:30:00,199
(Meanwhile, Kim Eun Hee was making the last touches.)

633
00:30:00,200 --> 00:30:03,210
The garlic. The Garlic Goddess's bread is going in the oven.

634
00:30:12,310 --> 00:30:14,020
I'm trying to overwhelm with the smell first.

635
00:30:15,850 --> 00:30:16,850
(Adding truffle oil)

636
00:30:17,450 --> 00:30:18,450
(More truffle oil)

637
00:30:19,150 --> 00:30:20,760
Where is the truffle smell coming from?

638
00:30:21,690 --> 00:30:22,690
Gosh.

639
00:30:23,060 --> 00:30:24,430
The smell is filling up this space.

640
00:30:25,890 --> 00:30:26,900
This feels like swindling.

641
00:30:26,960 --> 00:30:28,529
(If you add cream cheese...)

642
00:30:28,530 --> 00:30:31,500
(and pepper,)

643
00:30:32,170 --> 00:30:36,410
(garlic bread that conquered Gwangjang Market is complete.)

644
00:30:37,970 --> 00:30:38,970
I'm nervous.

645
00:30:40,740 --> 00:30:44,510
(Bake Your Dream)

646
00:30:44,980 --> 00:30:47,420
(Breathing out)

647
00:30:49,890 --> 00:30:50,990
I'm off for evaluation.

648
00:30:52,950 --> 00:30:57,060
(She's starting off as the first one.)

649
00:31:00,360 --> 00:31:01,430
She's going.

650
00:31:01,830 --> 00:31:03,330
She's going in?

651
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:06,440
(Gosh)

652
00:31:12,640 --> 00:31:15,840
(The first bread is on the conveyor belt.)

653
00:31:16,510 --> 00:31:18,450
(Gwangjang Market Garlic Goddess, Kim Eun Hee)

654
00:31:18,880 --> 00:31:20,680
- It's here. - Yes.

655
00:31:24,150 --> 00:31:28,520
Finally, the first contender's bread is coming in.

656
00:31:31,960 --> 00:31:34,459
I wanted to submit it when it's at its best condition.

657
00:31:34,460 --> 00:31:37,900
And I wanted to be evaluated as it is.

658
00:31:44,740 --> 00:31:46,010
That is scary.

659
00:31:47,980 --> 00:31:50,150
The first bread is making its way in.

660
00:31:51,350 --> 00:31:52,880
- Oh, gosh. - Yes.

661
00:31:53,720 --> 00:31:55,320
She must be nervous as it is the first evaluation.

662
00:31:58,390 --> 00:32:01,660
(First evaluation, Truffle cream garlic bread)

663
00:32:03,830 --> 00:32:06,930
Gosh. Yes.

664
00:32:07,430 --> 00:32:08,460
Gosh.

665
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:10,070
Goodness.

666
00:32:10,200 --> 00:32:11,229
(The strong punch of the scent of garlic bread)

667
00:32:11,230 --> 00:32:12,800
You can smell everything.

668
00:32:15,370 --> 00:32:16,370
Okay.

669
00:32:21,310 --> 00:32:23,150
Contender, please come in.

670
00:32:26,280 --> 00:32:28,280
- Go for it. - Good job.

671
00:32:31,490 --> 00:32:32,790
Go for it.

672
00:32:33,390 --> 00:32:35,890
(Gwangjang Market Garlic Goddess, Kim Eun Hee)

673
00:32:36,560 --> 00:32:37,989
Hello.

674
00:32:37,990 --> 00:32:39,930
- Hello. - Hello.

675
00:32:41,730 --> 00:32:43,829
Please introduce yourself...

676
00:32:43,830 --> 00:32:46,699
and introduce your signature bread.

677
00:32:46,700 --> 00:32:50,269
I'm Gwangjang Market Garlic Goddess, Kim Eun Hee.

678
00:32:50,270 --> 00:32:52,970
I run Garlic Boy at Gwangjang Market.

679
00:32:53,310 --> 00:32:57,050
The signature menu is truffle cream garlic bread.

680
00:32:57,450 --> 00:33:01,179
Garlic, cream, and truffle oil blend harmoniously.

681
00:33:01,180 --> 00:33:04,389
I sought to create "new..."

682
00:33:04,390 --> 00:33:06,890
and "new garlic bread" sensation in one bite.

683
00:33:07,290 --> 00:33:09,689
I heard that this was the first bakery...

684
00:33:09,690 --> 00:33:12,129
that was created in 120 years at Gwangjang Market. Is that so?

685
00:33:12,130 --> 00:33:15,000
Yes. I run the first bakery at Gwangjang Market.

686
00:33:16,830 --> 00:33:19,870
Shall we discuss this while tasting it?

687
00:33:46,390 --> 00:33:48,029
How much is this?

688
00:33:48,030 --> 00:33:49,459
It's 5.3 dollars.

689
00:33:49,460 --> 00:33:50,900
- It's 5.3 dollars? - Yes.

690
00:34:09,920 --> 00:34:12,819
Masters, have you all had a taste? How is it?

691
00:34:12,820 --> 00:34:15,919
I'm the type of person...

692
00:34:15,920 --> 00:34:18,890
who doesn't have much opinion on truffle oil.

693
00:34:22,830 --> 00:34:27,739
But I felt the oil taste was too strong when I ate it.

694
00:34:27,740 --> 00:34:31,440
If I ask you to eat this all by yourself, can you eat it all?

695
00:34:32,710 --> 00:34:33,710
This?

696
00:34:34,010 --> 00:34:36,609
I don't sell them right after it's made.

697
00:34:36,610 --> 00:34:40,179
The scent is weakened after a while.

698
00:34:40,180 --> 00:34:42,050
If that is the condition, I could eat two.

699
00:34:42,680 --> 00:34:44,220
(Right.)

700
00:34:49,890 --> 00:34:51,789
When it comes to garlic bread,

701
00:34:51,790 --> 00:34:55,159
most people think of hard garlic crust bread,

702
00:34:55,160 --> 00:34:59,029
but this is my first time trying soft garlic bread.

703
00:34:59,030 --> 00:35:01,539
Is there a reason for using pepper?

704
00:35:01,540 --> 00:35:04,969
Garlic, cream, and truffle oil are...

705
00:35:04,970 --> 00:35:06,369
incredibly heavy in themselves.

706
00:35:06,370 --> 00:35:07,809
I added some acidity to the cream...

707
00:35:07,810 --> 00:35:11,209
and pepper to finish it off,

708
00:35:11,210 --> 00:35:12,210
to give it a little more balance.

709
00:35:12,880 --> 00:35:16,719
I think the use of pepper became a point.

710
00:35:16,720 --> 00:35:20,859
I think it was a point to the taste of garlic and truffle.

711
00:35:20,860 --> 00:35:21,920
Thank you.

712
00:35:22,260 --> 00:35:24,789
This is bread that people either love or hate.

713
00:35:24,790 --> 00:35:28,630
But seeing that there was a person who liked it, made me confident.

714
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:30,930
Master Kwon Sung Jun, what do you think?

715
00:35:31,230 --> 00:35:33,069
Personally, I think this is a good item...

716
00:35:33,070 --> 00:35:35,439
in the market.

717
00:35:35,440 --> 00:35:38,339
The market itself is filled with smells like grease, fried food,

718
00:35:38,340 --> 00:35:41,209
- tteokbokki, and intestines... - Yes.

719
00:35:41,210 --> 00:35:43,079
It's filled with all kinds of smell,

720
00:35:43,080 --> 00:35:46,310
so I think this level of intensity is acceptable.

721
00:35:46,720 --> 00:35:49,650
But outside of the market, in a studio like this,

722
00:35:50,290 --> 00:35:51,549
it's actually a bit overpowering.

723
00:35:51,550 --> 00:35:54,389
I think it would be a good idea to adjust the balance a bit.

724
00:35:54,390 --> 00:35:55,490
Thank you.

725
00:35:56,730 --> 00:36:00,800
Masters, please make your votes.

726
00:36:03,670 --> 00:36:06,969
If you have made your decision, please press the button.

727
00:36:06,970 --> 00:36:07,970
(You need more than half of the votes from 5 to survive.)

728
00:36:08,640 --> 00:36:09,770
I'm confident.

729
00:36:09,970 --> 00:36:13,380
It has the charm of stimulating the sense of smell.

730
00:36:13,480 --> 00:36:16,239
We will check the results for contender Kim Eun Hee,

731
00:36:16,240 --> 00:36:20,350
the Gwangjang Market Garlic Goddess.

732
00:36:20,420 --> 00:36:23,420
(What choice have the 5 Masters made?)

733
00:36:24,250 --> 00:36:26,520
If the bread passes through the Pass Zone, it's a fail.

734
00:36:26,960 --> 00:36:28,720
If the bread stops at the Pass Zone,

735
00:36:29,790 --> 00:36:30,930
it is a pass.

736
00:36:31,730 --> 00:36:34,630
What will the result be?

737
00:36:39,600 --> 00:36:44,340
(The Masters had a difference of opinion.)

738
00:36:46,210 --> 00:36:49,740
(What is the result for the truffle cream garlic bread?)

739
00:36:51,980 --> 00:36:53,850
(Kim Eun Hee is eliminated.)

740
00:36:56,120 --> 00:36:59,520
Unfortunately, Contender Kim Eun Hee is eliminated.

741
00:37:00,290 --> 00:37:02,860
(Gwangjang Market Garlic Goddess, Kim Eun Hee, Fail)

742
00:37:03,390 --> 00:37:04,530
Oh, gosh.

743
00:37:08,900 --> 00:37:10,099
It is the same with life.

744
00:37:10,100 --> 00:37:11,430
It's not something that I can control.

745
00:37:12,330 --> 00:37:13,770
It's not something that I can control.

746
00:37:14,170 --> 00:37:17,670
Unfortunately, Contender Kim Eun Hee is eliminated.

747
00:37:18,770 --> 00:37:21,939
Truffle oil is fat, right?

748
00:37:21,940 --> 00:37:23,649
But cream cheese is also fat.

749
00:37:23,650 --> 00:37:26,879
When these two were mixed,

750
00:37:26,880 --> 00:37:28,319
the cream's texture separated.

751
00:37:28,320 --> 00:37:30,189
That was a little disappointing.

752
00:37:30,190 --> 00:37:32,249
It would've been better without the truffle oil.

753
00:37:32,250 --> 00:37:33,590
Yes, it would have been better.

754
00:37:34,020 --> 00:37:36,319
I do plan to open a second...

755
00:37:36,320 --> 00:37:37,689
and a third store.

756
00:37:37,690 --> 00:37:39,059
I will incorporate all the feedback...

757
00:37:39,060 --> 00:37:41,730
and show you that I could flourish.

758
00:37:41,900 --> 00:37:42,960
Thank you.

759
00:37:43,160 --> 00:37:44,400
Well done.

760
00:37:45,630 --> 00:37:48,139
I was a little disappointed.

761
00:37:48,140 --> 00:37:52,109
But I had the tendency of being too one-sided.

762
00:37:52,110 --> 00:37:55,079
So I thought, "I should study hard..."

763
00:37:55,080 --> 00:37:56,310
"and continuously to survive."

764
00:37:56,810 --> 00:37:59,410
(Meanwhile)

765
00:38:09,060 --> 00:38:12,229
The tiramisu that you break to eat is broken already.

766
00:38:12,230 --> 00:38:14,500
- This is a broken heart. - It's a broken heart.

767
00:38:15,460 --> 00:38:17,700
- Shall we taste it? - Yes.

768
00:38:18,400 --> 00:38:22,499
This heart is broken. Is there a meaning to this?

769
00:38:22,500 --> 00:38:23,510
Honestly,

770
00:38:30,080 --> 00:38:33,379
I failed with the tempering this time.

771
00:38:33,380 --> 00:38:34,649
(Tempering)

772
00:38:34,650 --> 00:38:36,080
(The process of hardening chocolate after melting it)

773
00:38:36,150 --> 00:38:38,120
(30 minutes earlier)

774
00:38:39,990 --> 00:38:41,620
It's too hot.

775
00:38:42,360 --> 00:38:44,430
The ganache didn't harden at all.

776
00:38:45,060 --> 00:38:47,729
It's okay. It didn't harden. What can I do about it?

777
00:38:47,730 --> 00:38:48,730
(The ganache, the chocolate cream, is running down like liquid.)

778
00:38:53,070 --> 00:38:55,070
Gosh. It broke.

779
00:38:55,200 --> 00:38:57,640
(Even the heart-shaped chocolate shells broke.)

780
00:38:57,770 --> 00:39:00,379
When I worked on it on the set,

781
00:39:00,380 --> 00:39:03,239
the set was too hot, so it didn't break...

782
00:39:03,240 --> 00:39:05,080
as well as I hoped.

783
00:39:05,280 --> 00:39:09,480
So the tempering didn't go well.

784
00:39:19,760 --> 00:39:23,000
Honestly, it's not the type of tiramisu that I favor.

785
00:39:23,460 --> 00:39:25,730
This is bread-like tiramisu.

786
00:39:27,470 --> 00:39:32,040
Isn't it a bit too hard to be considered tiramisu?

787
00:39:33,940 --> 00:39:37,450
Actually, to call this...

788
00:39:38,880 --> 00:39:41,480
tiramisu, the cream...

789
00:39:45,750 --> 00:39:47,160
To me...

790
00:39:48,120 --> 00:39:50,690
How should I say this? It's too light?

791
00:39:52,360 --> 00:39:53,700
It's a bit light.

792
00:39:53,900 --> 00:39:55,459
It lacks sweetness too.

793
00:39:55,460 --> 00:39:56,970
So it doesn't taste...

794
00:39:57,730 --> 00:40:00,200
balanced.

795
00:40:00,470 --> 00:40:04,769
It might've been better if it was richer and thicker.

796
00:40:04,770 --> 00:40:06,670
That's what I personally think.

797
00:40:07,180 --> 00:40:09,279
(Heart Maker Na Su Ji, fail)

798
00:40:09,280 --> 00:40:11,280
- You're eliminated. - Thank you.

799
00:40:11,380 --> 00:40:13,050
Please leave the bread factory.

800
00:40:13,150 --> 00:40:14,779
- Thank you for your hard work. - Thank you for your hard work.

801
00:40:14,780 --> 00:40:16,420
- Thank you. - Thank you.

802
00:40:16,680 --> 00:40:18,220
I guess I didn't work hard enough.

803
00:40:18,320 --> 00:40:21,819
"Is there anything I can add to make it more impactful?"

804
00:40:21,820 --> 00:40:23,959
I focused on things like that,

805
00:40:23,960 --> 00:40:27,900
so it ended up as slightly unconventional tiramisu.

806
00:40:28,060 --> 00:40:30,830
I shouldn't have been too greedy.

807
00:40:32,770 --> 00:40:36,270
I visit a lot of popular bakeries.

808
00:40:36,700 --> 00:40:39,370
I went to Mangwon-dong often for the Bakery Tour.

809
00:40:39,570 --> 00:40:41,309
People were lined up before the bakery opened.

810
00:40:41,310 --> 00:40:44,350
That place is popular.

811
00:40:44,610 --> 00:40:47,180
You need to wait a long time to enter the bakery.

812
00:40:47,550 --> 00:40:49,219
It's called Ugly Bakery.

813
00:40:49,220 --> 00:40:51,319
I was surprised to see him here.

814
00:40:51,320 --> 00:40:52,549
Butter Bakery.

815
00:40:52,550 --> 00:40:55,359
I went to Butter Bakery many times.

816
00:40:55,360 --> 00:40:56,759
I've heard about it.

817
00:40:56,760 --> 00:40:59,629
He's like a deity to us.

818
00:40:59,630 --> 00:41:00,759
I know him.

819
00:41:00,760 --> 00:41:02,199
He is well-known for his croissants.

820
00:41:02,200 --> 00:41:03,730
I went and bought his pastries.

821
00:41:03,970 --> 00:41:05,069
All the popular bakers are here.

822
00:41:05,070 --> 00:41:06,070
I queued up for Ugly Bakery...

823
00:41:06,071 --> 00:41:08,370
even before it became super popular.

824
00:41:08,640 --> 00:41:10,170
Even before it became this popular.

825
00:41:13,170 --> 00:41:15,279
Oh, Breadwon-dong.

826
00:41:15,280 --> 00:41:16,780
He is Bread Boss.

827
00:41:17,610 --> 00:41:19,409
Hello. I'm running Ugly Bakery...

828
00:41:19,410 --> 00:41:21,949
in Mangwon-dong, Seoul, for eight years.

829
00:41:21,950 --> 00:41:24,020
I'm Mangwon-dong Bread Boss, Jeong Jeong Hun.

830
00:41:24,220 --> 00:41:25,719
The bread I prepared...

831
00:41:25,720 --> 00:41:27,820
has tons of famine crops.

832
00:41:28,220 --> 00:41:29,989
Many of my products...

833
00:41:29,990 --> 00:41:32,490
have more sub-materials than the dough itself.

834
00:41:32,760 --> 00:41:35,400
I thought I could express their uniqueness with this.

835
00:41:35,430 --> 00:41:38,370
That's how I prepared Famine Crops Lover.

836
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:42,070
(He starts peeling sweet potatoes, the main famine crop.)

837
00:41:42,600 --> 00:41:45,970
We use sweet potatoes, chestnuts, sweet pumpkin, and many more.

838
00:41:46,470 --> 00:41:49,710
We cut the ingredients ourselves and add plenty of them.

839
00:41:51,550 --> 00:41:54,419
The bakery is so popular.

840
00:41:54,420 --> 00:41:57,490
He must take pride in it.

841
00:41:57,820 --> 00:41:59,720
The point of Famine Crops Lover...

842
00:42:00,090 --> 00:42:03,660
is that there are more ingredients than the dough.

843
00:42:04,390 --> 00:42:08,129
I prepared 50g of dough today.

844
00:42:08,130 --> 00:42:10,630
The fillings are almost 250g.

845
00:42:11,900 --> 00:42:14,439
The pastry that shocked me when I tried it...

846
00:42:14,440 --> 00:42:15,569
was the one from Ugly Bakery.

847
00:42:15,570 --> 00:42:19,070
"You can go this far with bread."

848
00:42:19,310 --> 00:42:21,980
He made me realize how far the concept of bread can expand.

849
00:42:23,080 --> 00:42:25,379
That's the point. Heaps of toppings.

850
00:42:25,380 --> 00:42:27,419
He adds heaps of Korean-style toppings.

851
00:42:27,420 --> 00:42:28,679
- Because social media... - That's right.

852
00:42:28,680 --> 00:42:30,719
is the main mode of promotions, so its visual...

853
00:42:30,720 --> 00:42:33,219
That's right. Now, rather than its taste,

854
00:42:33,220 --> 00:42:34,519
whether it looks photo-worthy...

855
00:42:34,520 --> 00:42:35,890
- comes first. - Yes.

856
00:42:36,020 --> 00:42:37,530
But nowadays...

857
00:42:37,960 --> 00:42:39,560
Isn't it...

858
00:42:40,500 --> 00:42:41,960
a bit too much nowadays?

859
00:42:42,500 --> 00:42:43,700
They do add a lot of things.

860
00:42:45,630 --> 00:42:47,600
(Will they become breads that catered to the trend as well?)

861
00:42:47,800 --> 00:42:49,900
(Or will they become breads that only catered to the trend?)

862
00:42:51,740 --> 00:42:53,270
That's a lot.

863
00:42:53,410 --> 00:42:55,340
- He wraps it like that. - Yes.

864
00:42:57,280 --> 00:42:59,510
I have no idea how it will turn out.

865
00:43:00,050 --> 00:43:02,080
Who knows how it will taste?

866
00:43:03,080 --> 00:43:06,920
The bread is crude and ugly.

867
00:43:07,090 --> 00:43:09,960
When you cut it in half and look at the cross section or eat it,

868
00:43:10,020 --> 00:43:11,929
it has an unexpected twist,

869
00:43:11,930 --> 00:43:14,930
so I prepared this bread.

870
00:43:16,900 --> 00:43:19,400
(Mangwon-dong Bread Boss, Jeong Jeong Hun)

871
00:43:19,570 --> 00:43:22,099
Please explain your signature bread.

872
00:43:22,100 --> 00:43:23,970
The signature bread I prepared...

873
00:43:24,240 --> 00:43:26,770
makes use of famine crops.

874
00:43:26,970 --> 00:43:29,640
It has sweet potatoes, sweet pumpkins, and chestnuts.

875
00:43:30,550 --> 00:43:33,149
It has the right amount of red beans and cream cheese,

876
00:43:33,150 --> 00:43:36,149
so it tastes mild but not too plain.

877
00:43:36,150 --> 00:43:37,350
That's what I focused on.

878
00:43:39,150 --> 00:43:40,690
Its biggest characteristic is...

879
00:43:41,120 --> 00:43:45,629
that it has more sub-ingredients than the dough.

880
00:43:45,630 --> 00:43:48,799
Not only does it have a lot of ingredients,

881
00:43:48,800 --> 00:43:52,429
but I believe I managed to secure the right balance as well.

882
00:43:52,430 --> 00:43:54,439
So I prepared this bread with confidence.

883
00:43:54,440 --> 00:43:57,170
- I see. Let's try the bread. - Okay.

884
00:44:14,920 --> 00:44:16,890
I thought, "It won't be easy."

885
00:44:22,500 --> 00:44:24,399
I definitely think...

886
00:44:24,400 --> 00:44:27,000
some judges would like it and some wouldn't.

887
00:44:29,970 --> 00:44:32,710
So I was curious to find out how they would take it.

888
00:44:39,680 --> 00:44:41,020
For the chestnuts,

889
00:44:41,820 --> 00:44:43,079
you didn't use canned ones.

890
00:44:43,080 --> 00:44:45,189
- You peeled them yourself. - Yes.

891
00:44:45,190 --> 00:44:47,050
I made the red bean paste,

892
00:44:47,160 --> 00:44:48,589
boiled down the chestnuts,

893
00:44:48,590 --> 00:44:50,690
and boiled the sweet pumpkins and sweet potatoes myself.

894
00:44:50,860 --> 00:44:53,830
A lot of effort goes into the bread.

895
00:44:53,860 --> 00:44:55,559
How much does this bread cost?

896
00:44:55,560 --> 00:44:56,699
It costs 5.50 dollars.

897
00:44:56,700 --> 00:44:58,029
- It's 5.50 dollars? - Yes.

898
00:44:58,030 --> 00:44:59,570
If you sell it at 5.50 dollars,

899
00:45:00,400 --> 00:45:01,600
- can you make a profit? - Right.

900
00:45:02,270 --> 00:45:04,840
Increasing the price by 10 or 20 cents...

901
00:45:05,070 --> 00:45:08,239
because the cost of ingredients went up is hard to do.

902
00:45:08,240 --> 00:45:10,710
I'm trying my best to find the answer within this.

903
00:45:11,450 --> 00:45:14,580
I understand why people would queue up for this.

904
00:45:15,620 --> 00:45:18,320
What I think is...

905
00:45:19,650 --> 00:45:20,690
This...

906
00:45:21,360 --> 00:45:23,690
The theme is bread, but where is bread?

907
00:45:24,290 --> 00:45:25,429
(Master Lee Seok Won points out sharply.)

908
00:45:25,430 --> 00:45:27,330
It makes me think, "Where is bread?"

909
00:45:27,860 --> 00:45:29,560
Everything else is tasty.

910
00:45:30,030 --> 00:45:32,230
Each ingredient is delicious,

911
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:36,200
but this is about baking bread, and I see no bread.

912
00:45:36,470 --> 00:45:38,340
- You're right. - It's a bit of a shame.

913
00:45:39,040 --> 00:45:40,069
(Masters have contrary opinions on his bread.)

914
00:45:40,070 --> 00:45:42,780
Let's check the result.

915
00:45:45,180 --> 00:45:48,050
(What choice did the 5 masters make?)

916
00:45:49,520 --> 00:45:50,820
I was worried.

917
00:45:51,620 --> 00:45:54,520
I thought they'd be split exactly into half.

918
00:45:55,160 --> 00:45:58,059
If the remaining one person sides with me, I'll pass.

919
00:45:58,060 --> 00:45:59,629
But if that one person doesn't side with me,

920
00:45:59,630 --> 00:46:02,000
I'll fail for sure. That's what I thought.

921
00:46:06,000 --> 00:46:09,800
(What's the result of Famine Crops Lover?)

922
00:46:13,010 --> 00:46:15,380
(Mangwon-dong Bread Boss Jeong Jeong Hun passed.)

923
00:46:16,940 --> 00:46:19,550
You passed.

924
00:46:19,980 --> 00:46:22,079
Please continue to bake your dream.

925
00:46:22,080 --> 00:46:23,249
Congratulations.

926
00:46:23,250 --> 00:46:24,349
Thank you.

927
00:46:24,350 --> 00:46:26,549
- Thank you. - It tastes even better today.

928
00:46:26,550 --> 00:46:27,560
Thank you.

929
00:46:28,490 --> 00:46:29,959
Thank you.

930
00:46:29,960 --> 00:46:30,990
It's delicious.

931
00:46:33,090 --> 00:46:37,500
(The passed signature breads can be displayed in the Hall of Fame.)

932
00:46:37,530 --> 00:46:40,569
I wanted to let people know what kind of bread we baked,

933
00:46:40,570 --> 00:46:42,699
and that breads like this are quite charming too.

934
00:46:42,700 --> 00:46:44,810
That's why I joined the show.

935
00:46:45,340 --> 00:46:46,839
And they acknowledged it.

936
00:46:46,840 --> 00:46:48,779
So I'm very happy.

937
00:46:48,780 --> 00:46:52,010
I'll do my best to get good results.

938
00:46:52,610 --> 00:46:54,180
(Pass)

939
00:46:54,380 --> 00:46:56,950
(The news of the first passer is delivered to everyone.)

940
00:46:57,220 --> 00:46:58,549
It's okay, it's just one person.

941
00:46:58,550 --> 00:47:00,250
I think it's my first time hearing that music.

942
00:47:01,060 --> 00:47:04,060
"I don't want to lose." My competitive spirit is boiling.

943
00:47:04,360 --> 00:47:06,760
I want to do my best.

944
00:47:07,130 --> 00:47:08,960
All I can do is give it my all.

945
00:47:11,030 --> 00:47:13,800
(After the first passer, the contenders start to speed up.)

946
00:47:15,340 --> 00:47:17,769
(But there's steam rising from one place?)

947
00:47:17,770 --> 00:47:18,839
What's that?

948
00:47:18,840 --> 00:47:20,270
(But there's steam rising from one place?)

949
00:47:20,440 --> 00:47:22,980
- It's a steamer. - It's a steamer.

950
00:47:23,040 --> 00:47:24,349
The way she works...

951
00:47:24,350 --> 00:47:27,319
clearly isn't that of a typical baker.

952
00:47:27,320 --> 00:47:28,949
She used to make rice cakes.

953
00:47:28,950 --> 00:47:30,220
- Rice cakes? - Yes.

954
00:47:30,320 --> 00:47:32,849
Hello, I'm Mill Baker Jeong Nam Mi...

955
00:47:32,850 --> 00:47:35,860
from Gangneung.

956
00:47:36,190 --> 00:47:38,530
I ran a rice cake shop for 35 years,

957
00:47:38,630 --> 00:47:41,860
then I sold bread for 5 years, so it's a total of 40 years.

958
00:47:44,230 --> 00:47:47,070
People are starting to forget rice cakes.

959
00:47:47,200 --> 00:47:49,539
When I present bread and rice cake to young people,

960
00:47:49,540 --> 00:47:52,470
they go for bread, not rice cake.

961
00:47:54,010 --> 00:47:57,480
Things will slowly change that way.

962
00:47:57,610 --> 00:47:59,310
That's how I started.

963
00:47:59,750 --> 00:48:01,349
This is a famous bakery.

964
00:48:01,350 --> 00:48:03,880
She bakes using famine crops, and it's really delicious.

965
00:48:04,190 --> 00:48:06,149
Orders are backed up due to high volume,

966
00:48:06,150 --> 00:48:07,590
so we've blocked online orders.

967
00:48:09,320 --> 00:48:11,160
We've become known now.

968
00:48:11,830 --> 00:48:13,130
We opened pop-up stores,

969
00:48:14,230 --> 00:48:16,799
went to Singapore and Taiwan,

970
00:48:16,800 --> 00:48:18,599
and set up a store in Japan too.

971
00:48:18,600 --> 00:48:19,699
(Contender Jeong Nam Mi...)

972
00:48:19,700 --> 00:48:22,200
(went around the world with her bread.)

973
00:48:22,400 --> 00:48:23,969
I only use farm produce.

974
00:48:23,970 --> 00:48:26,040
I don't use processed food.

975
00:48:26,910 --> 00:48:30,010
I wash, cut, and steam them myself.

976
00:48:32,610 --> 00:48:34,579
It's neither rice cake nor bread.

977
00:48:34,580 --> 00:48:37,590
It has the taste of nature as is.

978
00:48:40,590 --> 00:48:41,660
I'm looking forward to it.

979
00:48:42,060 --> 00:48:44,090
What is she doing now?

980
00:48:45,960 --> 00:48:46,960
They're all steamed.

981
00:48:46,961 --> 00:48:49,060
She steamed the famine crops, not rice cakes.

982
00:48:49,800 --> 00:48:52,430
Eighty percent of the farm produce I use is from Gangneung.

983
00:48:53,170 --> 00:48:54,940
Chestnut bread uses chestnuts,

984
00:48:55,470 --> 00:48:57,170
pumpkin bread uses pumpkins,

985
00:48:57,910 --> 00:49:00,239
and corn bread uses corns.

986
00:49:00,240 --> 00:49:02,180
The whole crop is added.

987
00:49:03,480 --> 00:49:05,580
She used the ones she carried on the tray.

988
00:49:05,750 --> 00:49:06,909
- The tray just now. - The tray.

989
00:49:06,910 --> 00:49:07,950
From just now.

990
00:49:08,380 --> 00:49:11,120
She carried the tray on her head.

991
00:49:11,350 --> 00:49:15,590
She carried all the ingredients that goes into her bread.

992
00:49:15,920 --> 00:49:17,859
Right. I guess she's using those.

993
00:49:17,860 --> 00:49:20,460
(The ingredients on the tray went into the steamer.)

994
00:49:20,730 --> 00:49:21,730
Hello.

995
00:49:21,731 --> 00:49:23,159
- Hello. - Hi.

996
00:49:23,160 --> 00:49:25,429
I saw you come in with the tray on your head.

997
00:49:25,430 --> 00:49:26,500
Did you?

998
00:49:27,030 --> 00:49:28,969
There are so many ingredients that it's hard to keep track.

999
00:49:28,970 --> 00:49:30,699
What's this?

1000
00:49:30,700 --> 00:49:33,069
- It's the filling for leek bread. - Leek bread.

1001
00:49:33,070 --> 00:49:34,240
- The filling. - This is the dough.

1002
00:49:34,440 --> 00:49:35,679
- This is the dough? - Yes.

1003
00:49:35,680 --> 00:49:37,010
Do you want to see me wrap it?

1004
00:49:37,140 --> 00:49:38,310
I'll see it and then leave.

1005
00:49:40,650 --> 00:49:44,949
(Using green and white dough at the same time)

1006
00:49:44,950 --> 00:49:47,019
Do you use both doughs together?

1007
00:49:47,020 --> 00:49:48,060
Yes, like this.

1008
00:49:48,420 --> 00:49:49,960
This is how you make leek bread.

1009
00:49:50,520 --> 00:49:51,959
- The shape of leek. - Yes, leek bread.

1010
00:49:51,960 --> 00:49:53,160
- Is that it? - Yes.

1011
00:49:53,660 --> 00:49:55,199
Like this.

1012
00:49:55,200 --> 00:49:58,600
Once this is complete, I add some bean powder to look like soil.

1013
00:49:58,900 --> 00:50:01,100
- I see. - I add some bean powder.

1014
00:50:01,340 --> 00:50:03,339
I extracted perilla oil myself.

1015
00:50:03,340 --> 00:50:05,509
(She expressed soil with the perilla oil she extracted.)

1016
00:50:05,510 --> 00:50:07,039
- I can already see... - Like this.

1017
00:50:07,040 --> 00:50:08,240
the color and the shape.

1018
00:50:08,380 --> 00:50:10,180
Perilla oil goes well with steamed food.

1019
00:50:10,380 --> 00:50:11,409
Yes.

1020
00:50:11,410 --> 00:50:13,650
(She received high expectations.)

1021
00:50:14,880 --> 00:50:18,720
She always makes it into the shape of the ingredient.

1022
00:50:19,690 --> 00:50:20,989
Isn't that sweet paste?

1023
00:50:20,990 --> 00:50:24,120
(Chili sweet paste in chili bread)

1024
00:50:24,690 --> 00:50:26,130
It's chili-shaped.

1025
00:50:26,730 --> 00:50:28,000
- That's corn. - It looks like a sweet potato.

1026
00:50:29,200 --> 00:50:32,430
She must've made the silicon mold herself too.

1027
00:50:33,770 --> 00:50:35,470
(The surface of corn using a silicon mold)

1028
00:50:35,800 --> 00:50:36,800
What's that?

1029
00:50:36,801 --> 00:50:38,039
- They're pumpkins. - How pretty.

1030
00:50:38,040 --> 00:50:39,109
They're pumpkins.

1031
00:50:39,110 --> 00:50:41,539
They look like real pumpkins and real corns.

1032
00:50:41,540 --> 00:50:42,640
It's amazing.

1033
00:50:43,680 --> 00:50:44,880
They're all here.

1034
00:50:45,210 --> 00:50:46,449
That's such a great idea.

1035
00:50:46,450 --> 00:50:47,480
(Garlic, sweet potato, corn, chili, chestnut)

1036
00:50:47,620 --> 00:50:49,219
Young people nowadays love stuff like that.

1037
00:50:49,220 --> 00:50:51,150
They go crazy. People like me.

1038
00:50:52,620 --> 00:50:54,520
She has the most types of bread.

1039
00:50:54,660 --> 00:50:55,860
Most in volume too.

1040
00:50:56,790 --> 00:50:58,490
In terms of both color and shape,

1041
00:50:59,090 --> 00:51:01,530
this is what I'm most confident in, so I decided to bake it.

1042
00:51:03,300 --> 00:51:06,570
(Famine crop bread)

1043
00:51:07,800 --> 00:51:10,270
The next bread is coming in.

1044
00:51:11,170 --> 00:51:13,470
- It's finally here. - The anticipated bread.

1045
00:51:14,780 --> 00:51:17,780
- This is really... - It sure has a strong impact.

1046
00:51:18,710 --> 00:51:20,279
Please explain...

1047
00:51:20,280 --> 00:51:21,449
- Okay. - your signature bread.

1048
00:51:21,450 --> 00:51:23,220
Those breads...

1049
00:51:23,520 --> 00:51:25,820
are called famine crop bread.

1050
00:51:26,050 --> 00:51:29,859
All the ingredients are local farm produce.

1051
00:51:29,860 --> 00:51:30,860
(Local farm produce)

1052
00:51:31,130 --> 00:51:32,759
Pumpkin bread has pumpkin in it.

1053
00:51:32,760 --> 00:51:34,160
(Pumpkin paste)

1054
00:51:34,630 --> 00:51:36,830
Sweet potato bread has mashed sweet potato in it.

1055
00:51:37,600 --> 00:51:39,529
It's not just the shape, but the ingredients are inside too?

1056
00:51:39,530 --> 00:51:40,599
Yes.

1057
00:51:40,600 --> 00:51:43,269
Corn bread has steamed and mashed corn in it.

1058
00:51:43,270 --> 00:51:44,309
(The whole produce inside the famine crop bread)

1059
00:51:44,310 --> 00:51:45,510
It's in the bread.

1060
00:52:09,100 --> 00:52:10,300
During the evaluation,

1061
00:52:10,600 --> 00:52:12,970
for some reason, I started to lose my confidence.

1062
00:52:18,870 --> 00:52:20,909
The taste of the ingredients...

1063
00:52:20,910 --> 00:52:24,410
(The taste of the ingredients...)

1064
00:52:27,980 --> 00:52:32,390
The taste of each ingredient stands out well.

1065
00:52:32,720 --> 00:52:33,990
It's really good.

1066
00:52:34,820 --> 00:52:35,820
Thank you.

1067
00:52:37,020 --> 00:52:39,559
The corn used is waxy corn from Gangwon Province too.

1068
00:52:39,560 --> 00:52:40,790
Yes, from Gangwon Province.

1069
00:52:43,660 --> 00:52:46,230
(What do the other masters think?)

1070
00:52:46,500 --> 00:52:49,200
If you're given other missions...

1071
00:52:49,470 --> 00:52:51,939
that don't use famine crops,

1072
00:52:51,940 --> 00:52:54,440
can you make something different?

1073
00:52:55,010 --> 00:52:58,610
When the time comes, I'd like to make baekseolgi.

1074
00:52:59,250 --> 00:53:00,949
What if it's not baekseolgi?

1075
00:53:00,950 --> 00:53:02,950
You could have other missions.

1076
00:53:04,050 --> 00:53:05,490
I'll try my best.

1077
00:53:10,290 --> 00:53:12,490
They were very strict with their evaluations.

1078
00:53:12,890 --> 00:53:14,900
I only have five years of baking experience.

1079
00:53:15,030 --> 00:53:18,600
How could I win against the others?

1080
00:53:19,530 --> 00:53:20,870
I almost flopped down.

1081
00:53:21,740 --> 00:53:24,740
Let's check the result.

1082
00:53:25,940 --> 00:53:28,980
Mill Baker Jeong Nam Mi.

1083
00:53:29,440 --> 00:53:30,510
Did she pass?

1084
00:53:35,280 --> 00:53:38,090
(Is bringing out the natural taste her strength?)

1085
00:53:38,220 --> 00:53:40,550
(Is she worried about the contender's capability?)

1086
00:53:41,960 --> 00:53:44,220
(What's the result of Mill Baker?)

1087
00:53:46,130 --> 00:53:48,160
(Mill Baker Jeong Nam Mi passed.)

1088
00:53:49,930 --> 00:53:51,400
You passed.

1089
00:53:52,370 --> 00:53:53,999
Congratulations.

1090
00:53:54,000 --> 00:53:55,370
Congratulations.

1091
00:53:58,440 --> 00:53:59,540
Oh, dear.

1092
00:54:00,410 --> 00:54:01,809
You worked so hard.

1093
00:54:01,810 --> 00:54:03,880
- Yes, I did. - Good job.

1094
00:54:05,650 --> 00:54:08,049
Doing the same thing for 40 years in 1 place...

1095
00:54:08,050 --> 00:54:09,619
isn't easy in the food service industry.

1096
00:54:09,620 --> 00:54:10,680
It's difficult.

1097
00:54:10,980 --> 00:54:13,690
Statistically, only three percent...

1098
00:54:13,820 --> 00:54:15,190
lasts up to ten years.

1099
00:54:16,160 --> 00:54:17,930
- It's really... - Sorry?

1100
00:54:18,330 --> 00:54:19,930
- It's an incredible feat. - Thank you.

1101
00:54:20,290 --> 00:54:22,199
I'll continue to do my best.

1102
00:54:22,200 --> 00:54:23,660
(Her decades of hard work is acknowledged.)

1103
00:54:24,730 --> 00:54:26,470
- Which way do I exit? This way? - Yes, this way.

1104
00:54:28,140 --> 00:54:30,269
- My goodness. - She's like a little girl.

1105
00:54:30,270 --> 00:54:31,540
- She makes me tear up. - Yes.

1106
00:54:32,840 --> 00:54:36,480
"Famine crop" refers to all crops.

1107
00:54:37,750 --> 00:54:40,350
I want to let the whole world know about it.

1108
00:54:40,810 --> 00:54:42,150
I'll work harder.

1109
00:54:45,450 --> 00:54:49,220
(The passing alert sound resonates in the hall.)

1110
00:54:50,620 --> 00:54:52,160
- Amazing. - Amazing.

1111
00:54:54,230 --> 00:54:56,060
Isn't the sound very pretty too?

1112
00:54:56,600 --> 00:54:58,900
- The failing sound was scary. - Yes.

1113
00:54:59,800 --> 00:55:02,670
It shows whether they passed or failed right away.

1114
00:55:02,800 --> 00:55:04,669
So it makes me very nervous.

1115
00:55:04,670 --> 00:55:06,870
Still, since this is what I've been doing all this while,

1116
00:55:06,940 --> 00:55:09,310
I can do it.

1117
00:55:10,410 --> 00:55:12,079
(Will he be able to protect the pride...)

1118
00:55:12,080 --> 00:55:14,180
(of Yeonnam-dong Bakery Tour?)

1119
00:55:14,580 --> 00:55:17,420
(Scallion has charming tangy taste.)

1120
00:55:20,820 --> 00:55:21,820
What?

1121
00:55:22,520 --> 00:55:23,919
Isn't that scallion?

1122
00:55:23,920 --> 00:55:25,590
Isn't he making souffle?

1123
00:55:26,060 --> 00:55:27,459
Yes, he is making souffle.

1124
00:55:27,460 --> 00:55:28,799
(Souffle, a type of cake made using egg white foam...)

1125
00:55:28,800 --> 00:55:30,059
(and baked thickly)

1126
00:55:30,060 --> 00:55:32,629
Double-ion Souffle I'm making...

1127
00:55:32,630 --> 00:55:36,070
uses sweet and sour cream which has scallions and onions.

1128
00:55:36,270 --> 00:55:38,039
The cream is placed on souffle,

1129
00:55:38,040 --> 00:55:39,940
and it's the best bread.

1130
00:55:41,140 --> 00:55:44,509
He'll place it on a souffle cheesecake?

1131
00:55:44,510 --> 00:55:46,280
(Even the masters can't imagine how the combination will taste.)

1132
00:55:48,080 --> 00:55:50,319
For Double-ion Souffle,

1133
00:55:50,320 --> 00:55:52,620
I bake souffle cheesecake.

1134
00:55:53,950 --> 00:55:57,590
If I compare souffle to very soft rice,

1135
00:55:57,960 --> 00:56:01,060
double-ion cream is like a side dish.

1136
00:56:04,300 --> 00:56:05,699
Double-ion Souffle.

1137
00:56:05,700 --> 00:56:08,399
- Onion, scallion, - Onion and scallion.

1138
00:56:08,400 --> 00:56:09,669
- and souffle. - Double-ion Souffle.

1139
00:56:09,670 --> 00:56:11,340
I think that's why it's Double-ion Souffle.

1140
00:56:11,470 --> 00:56:12,770
What's that?

1141
00:56:15,510 --> 00:56:16,609
The 10,000-layer Croissant.

1142
00:56:16,610 --> 00:56:18,080
It's super popular on social media.

1143
00:56:19,080 --> 00:56:20,350
Reels and so on.

1144
00:56:24,350 --> 00:56:26,549
I had to keep using...

1145
00:56:26,550 --> 00:56:29,519
the pie roller for my pastry.

1146
00:56:29,520 --> 00:56:32,859
I had to spend 3 out of 4 hours...

1147
00:56:32,860 --> 00:56:35,800
using the machine.

1148
00:56:37,230 --> 00:56:39,529
Hello. I'm Jamsil's 10,000-layer Man,

1149
00:56:39,530 --> 00:56:40,700
Bang Jun Ho.

1150
00:56:40,900 --> 00:56:42,370
My signature bread...

1151
00:56:42,470 --> 00:56:45,240
is a croissant known as 10,000-layer Croissant.

1152
00:56:45,370 --> 00:56:48,009
The crispy texture is in harmony with the vanilla cream.

1153
00:56:48,010 --> 00:56:50,280
It's a crescent-shaped croissant.

1154
00:56:52,010 --> 00:56:55,620
As 10,000-layer Croissant became known,

1155
00:56:55,750 --> 00:56:57,649
I had 1,000 missed calls.

1156
00:56:57,650 --> 00:57:00,889
The phone became so hot that I couldn't hold it.

1157
00:57:00,890 --> 00:57:02,360
Everyone says it's delicious.

1158
00:57:05,930 --> 00:57:09,860
(How will he make 10,000-layer Croissant?)

1159
00:57:14,970 --> 00:57:17,399
(The dough is cut elaborately into same sizes.)

1160
00:57:17,400 --> 00:57:18,409
- My gosh. - Nice.

1161
00:57:18,410 --> 00:57:19,610
- It has 10,000 layers. - It has 10,000 layers.

1162
00:57:19,710 --> 00:57:22,709
I cut the dough thinly and pasted it on the surface.

1163
00:57:22,710 --> 00:57:25,349
By pasting it,

1164
00:57:25,350 --> 00:57:28,150
the pattern of 10,000 layers is made.

1165
00:57:28,550 --> 00:57:30,320
It's an important task.

1166
00:57:36,860 --> 00:57:38,330
- They're croissants. - Jamsil's 10,000-layer Man.

1167
00:57:39,530 --> 00:57:40,760
You're making croissants.

1168
00:57:40,890 --> 00:57:42,459
- The layers... - This...

1169
00:57:42,460 --> 00:57:44,460
- It has layers, right? - Yes.

1170
00:57:45,430 --> 00:57:47,199
Are there exactly 10,000 layers?

1171
00:57:47,200 --> 00:57:48,539
- No, it doesn't have 10,000 layers. - No?

1172
00:57:48,540 --> 00:57:49,869
It's not 10,000 layers.

1173
00:57:49,870 --> 00:57:52,469
Actually, it only has 46 layers.

1174
00:57:52,470 --> 00:57:54,909
But when it's baked,

1175
00:57:54,910 --> 00:57:58,180
it creates many wrinkles on the surface.

1176
00:58:03,620 --> 00:58:05,290
(Jamsil's 10,000-layer Man, Bang Jun Ho)

1177
00:58:10,860 --> 00:58:13,889
(10,000-layer Croissants are delivered to the masters.)

1178
00:58:13,890 --> 00:58:14,960
- But... - My gosh.

1179
00:58:15,460 --> 00:58:16,529
It looks amazing.

1180
00:58:16,530 --> 00:58:18,030
Can this even taste bad?

1181
00:58:19,870 --> 00:58:21,399
The signature bread I prepared today...

1182
00:58:21,400 --> 00:58:23,400
the 10,000-layer Croissant.

1183
00:58:24,140 --> 00:58:26,469
The outer layer is crispy,

1184
00:58:26,470 --> 00:58:29,110
while it is filled with vanilla cream inside.

1185
00:58:29,540 --> 00:58:31,310
(You cannot help but take pictures of this beauty.)

1186
00:58:37,380 --> 00:58:40,020
- We will now taste it. - Okay.

1187
00:58:42,020 --> 00:58:45,730
(They will try the vanilla cream first.)

1188
00:59:05,150 --> 00:59:08,249
- Did you brush baume syrup on it? - That's right.

1189
00:59:08,250 --> 00:59:10,149
I brushed on 30 baume syrup 30 minutes after it was baked.

1190
00:59:10,150 --> 00:59:11,689
(Baume syrup is a scale to identify...)

1191
00:59:11,690 --> 00:59:13,219
(the concentration of the sugar.)

1192
00:59:13,220 --> 00:59:14,790
(The sugar syrup coats the pastry once applied.)

1193
00:59:16,590 --> 00:59:18,789
I think that intensified...

1194
00:59:18,790 --> 00:59:20,290
- the crispiness. - Right.

1195
00:59:31,610 --> 00:59:34,810
- You filled in the cream very well. - Thank you.

1196
00:59:35,210 --> 00:59:37,709
"I did it." That thought came to mind.

1197
00:59:37,710 --> 00:59:40,049
I thought it was a good start.

1198
00:59:40,050 --> 00:59:42,320
I'm not sure if we can call this a croissant.

1199
00:59:45,720 --> 00:59:48,859
He folded many layers of the dough.

1200
00:59:48,860 --> 00:59:53,059
The dough was too concentrated where it was folded,

1201
00:59:53,060 --> 00:59:55,529
so the flour scent was too strong.

1202
00:59:55,530 --> 00:59:57,559
It's too bad.

1203
00:59:57,560 --> 00:59:58,600
I agree.

1204
00:59:58,630 --> 01:00:02,040
If you're done tasting it, let's check the result.

1205
01:00:04,640 --> 01:00:07,910
(What is the fate of the 10,000-layer Croissant?)

1206
01:00:10,310 --> 01:00:13,350
Jamsil's 10,000-layer Man. What will it be?

1207
01:00:17,880 --> 01:00:20,220
I'm so curious how it will taste.

1208
01:00:21,590 --> 01:00:23,860
I can't imagine it.

1209
01:00:25,860 --> 01:00:28,330
(Scallion and onion come together in the Double-ion Souffle)

1210
01:00:30,030 --> 01:00:33,229
Can you please tell us about your signature bread?

1211
01:00:33,230 --> 01:00:37,199
Sure. The signature bread I prepared...

1212
01:00:37,200 --> 01:00:39,239
is a souffle cheesecake.

1213
01:00:39,240 --> 01:00:41,709
On top of a moist souffle cheesecake,

1214
01:00:41,710 --> 01:00:44,909
there is cream made with scallions and onions.

1215
01:00:44,910 --> 01:00:46,709
It makes a refreshing taste.

1216
01:00:46,710 --> 01:00:50,079
What you see on top is popped Gouda.

1217
01:00:50,080 --> 01:00:53,720
It creates the salty taste, and it goes well with the cream.

1218
01:00:53,920 --> 01:00:55,990
I made such a cake.

1219
01:01:22,680 --> 01:01:26,549
Did you chop the scallions thick on purpose?

1220
01:01:26,550 --> 01:01:29,459
Yes, so you can chew on it. If I chop onions...

1221
01:01:29,460 --> 01:01:31,359
and scallions finely,

1222
01:01:31,360 --> 01:01:34,760
it will produce too much water. The cream would get watery.

1223
01:01:34,830 --> 01:01:37,659
That was why I chopped them thick.

1224
01:01:37,660 --> 01:01:40,669
I like the scallions big. Don't you?

1225
01:01:40,670 --> 01:01:42,040
That is what I don't like.

1226
01:01:42,540 --> 01:01:44,469
I like it because it felt like I was having bread with kimchi.

1227
01:01:44,470 --> 01:01:46,640
- With scallion kimchi? - Yes, I loved it.

1228
01:01:47,040 --> 01:01:48,240
I think...

1229
01:01:48,540 --> 01:01:50,979
I would prefer it on bread or a tart.

1230
01:01:50,980 --> 01:01:52,880
- Does it not go together? - Like a variation?

1231
01:01:53,210 --> 01:01:55,349
For me, the texture...

1232
01:01:55,350 --> 01:01:57,419
of the cake is too brittle.

1233
01:01:57,420 --> 01:01:59,849
(The texture of the cheesecake is not perfect.)

1234
01:01:59,850 --> 01:02:04,090
Okay. Yeonnam-dong Butter Man. Jamsil's 10,000-layer Man.

1235
01:02:04,620 --> 01:02:06,660
Let's check if they passed.

1236
01:02:11,100 --> 01:02:13,700
If the conveyor belt stops, they pass.

1237
01:02:15,170 --> 01:02:17,140
If it does not stop, they fail.

1238
01:02:19,270 --> 01:02:22,280
What will be the result?

1239
01:02:26,080 --> 01:02:27,579
Contender, you are eliminated.

1240
01:02:27,580 --> 01:02:28,849
- Too bad. - Yes.

1241
01:02:28,850 --> 01:02:30,320
(Which bread got eliminated?)

1242
01:02:36,860 --> 01:02:38,159
(Bang Jun Ho, fail)

1243
01:02:38,160 --> 01:02:39,290
(Kim Young Sik, fail)

1244
01:02:42,130 --> 01:02:44,929
- Kim Young Sik, you are eliminated. - Okay.

1245
01:02:44,930 --> 01:02:47,229
(Kim Young Sikand Bang Jun Ho both got eliminated.)

1246
01:02:47,230 --> 01:02:49,499
- Unfortunately, you got eliminated. - Okay.

1247
01:02:49,500 --> 01:02:52,070
Please leave the bread factory.

1248
01:02:53,540 --> 01:02:55,480
I'm a bit embarrassed.

1249
01:02:56,780 --> 01:02:59,779
Actually, I should have waited for it to rise more.

1250
01:02:59,780 --> 01:03:03,379
I should have taken more time.

1251
01:03:03,380 --> 01:03:06,719
I was pressed for time,

1252
01:03:06,720 --> 01:03:08,760
so the result was not satisfactory.

1253
01:03:09,890 --> 01:03:11,859
I knew it was possible to fail.

1254
01:03:11,860 --> 01:03:13,459
Everyone has different tastes.

1255
01:03:13,460 --> 01:03:16,499
I humbly accept their opinions,

1256
01:03:16,500 --> 01:03:19,869
but there are many people who enjoy my cake.

1257
01:03:19,870 --> 01:03:22,299
I find it tasty too, and that is why I sell it.

1258
01:03:22,300 --> 01:03:24,799
I want to make delicious cakes...

1259
01:03:24,800 --> 01:03:27,469
for those who find it to their liking.

1260
01:03:27,470 --> 01:03:29,379
That crossed my mind.

1261
01:03:29,380 --> 01:03:31,209
There are many variables to consider.

1262
01:03:31,210 --> 01:03:32,249
Right.

1263
01:03:32,250 --> 01:03:34,180
- It must be very difficult. - That is possible.

1264
01:03:34,610 --> 01:03:35,720
What is this?

1265
01:03:36,750 --> 01:03:37,880
What is he doing?

1266
01:03:38,290 --> 01:03:39,790
I think he's waiting for something.

1267
01:03:41,350 --> 01:03:43,990
(He is like a statue...)

1268
01:03:44,120 --> 01:03:47,230
(among the busy contenders.)

1269
01:03:47,830 --> 01:03:50,529
(Master of Selling Out, Lim Dong Seok)

1270
01:03:50,530 --> 01:03:51,930
Why is he frozen?

1271
01:03:52,730 --> 01:03:54,630
Why isn't he moving?

1272
01:03:55,170 --> 01:03:56,269
Chef Choi Gang Rok.

1273
01:03:56,270 --> 01:03:58,269
Yes, he's like Chef Choi Gang Rok.

1274
01:03:58,270 --> 01:04:00,539
- His facial expression too. - Master of Selling Out?

1275
01:04:00,540 --> 01:04:01,570
(They are somewhat similar.)

1276
01:04:01,740 --> 01:04:03,439
He must be fermenting it.

1277
01:04:03,440 --> 01:04:06,109
Yes, so he has nothing to do.

1278
01:04:06,110 --> 01:04:07,909
- It's in the fermentation cellar. - The fermentation cellar.

1279
01:04:07,910 --> 01:04:09,950
(The dough is going into the fermentation cellar.)

1280
01:04:10,220 --> 01:04:11,790
How much more do you need it to rise?

1281
01:04:12,090 --> 01:04:14,449
About a third more?

1282
01:04:14,450 --> 01:04:16,220
- About an hour? - An hour?

1283
01:04:16,360 --> 01:04:18,019
(Fermentation time)

1284
01:04:18,020 --> 01:04:20,489
(The dough rises during this key process...)

1285
01:04:20,490 --> 01:04:23,160
(which will determine the taste, scent, and texture.)

1286
01:04:23,830 --> 01:04:26,629
- Please, I beg you. - They're praying.

1287
01:04:26,630 --> 01:04:28,740
Gosh. You are right.

1288
01:04:29,270 --> 01:04:31,669
They are praying after putting it in the fermentation cellar.

1289
01:04:31,670 --> 01:04:33,910
- You can't help but pray. - Really?

1290
01:04:34,570 --> 01:04:36,509
From rising to baking.

1291
01:04:36,510 --> 01:04:37,510
You pray for a good turnout.

1292
01:04:37,640 --> 01:04:39,809
- It's the most important time. - Yes, it's about waiting.

1293
01:04:39,810 --> 01:04:41,720
The waiting game.

1294
01:04:42,380 --> 01:04:44,219
The taste depends on it, right?

1295
01:04:44,220 --> 01:04:46,219
Of course. These days,

1296
01:04:46,220 --> 01:04:47,789
- using levain is popular. - Natural.

1297
01:04:47,790 --> 01:04:49,559
- Natural leavening agent. - If you are leavening it naturally,

1298
01:04:49,560 --> 01:04:51,889
you work on it the night before and let it ferment.

1299
01:04:51,890 --> 01:04:53,529
You bake it the morning after.

1300
01:04:53,530 --> 01:04:55,560
Some places do it that way.

1301
01:04:55,930 --> 01:04:57,529
How long does it usually take?

1302
01:04:57,530 --> 01:04:59,529
It depends.

1303
01:04:59,530 --> 01:05:01,329
You should ferment for at least two hours.

1304
01:05:01,330 --> 01:05:02,699
- Two hours? - Yes.

1305
01:05:02,700 --> 01:05:05,110
(He intends to stand like this for 2 hours.)

1306
01:05:05,270 --> 01:05:08,309
Chef Lim Dong Seok is standing like a statue again.

1307
01:05:08,310 --> 01:05:10,280
- What a character. - Exactly.

1308
01:05:10,540 --> 01:05:11,879
I can't stop looking at him.

1309
01:05:11,880 --> 01:05:13,880
(Eye-catching)

1310
01:05:15,120 --> 01:05:16,679
(Whirring)

1311
01:05:16,680 --> 01:05:19,619
(He's attracting attention with loud noises.)

1312
01:05:19,620 --> 01:05:22,189
- It's Dessert Macho, Lee Kyung Mu. - Lee Kyung Mu.

1313
01:05:22,190 --> 01:05:23,359
He looks macho.

1314
01:05:23,360 --> 01:05:24,459
(Dessert Macho, Lee Kyung Mu)

1315
01:05:24,460 --> 01:05:25,760
(Runner-up, 2024 Coupe du Monde de la Boulangerie)

1316
01:05:26,130 --> 01:05:27,589
Why do you call yourself macho?

1317
01:05:27,590 --> 01:05:28,930
(Blazing eyes)

1318
01:05:36,370 --> 01:05:37,900
He's so scary.

1319
01:05:38,840 --> 01:05:41,010
He looks a bit scary.

1320
01:05:42,310 --> 01:05:44,809
(This contender draws attention with his looks.)

1321
01:05:44,810 --> 01:05:48,009
This person is a professional. He's very good.

1322
01:05:48,010 --> 01:05:49,019
Really?

1323
01:05:49,020 --> 01:05:52,049
He won second place at the biggest global competition...

1324
01:05:52,050 --> 01:05:56,259
in France. He won second in France with his bread.

1325
01:05:56,260 --> 01:05:58,120
(Coupe du Monde de la Boulangerie)

1326
01:05:58,260 --> 01:06:02,200
(Bakers each represent their nation at this global competition.)

1327
01:06:02,900 --> 01:06:04,000
South Korea.

1328
01:06:06,900 --> 01:06:09,070
(Dessert Macho, Lee Kyung Mu)

1329
01:06:15,280 --> 01:06:18,710
(A talented baker who won second at a global baking competition)

1330
01:06:18,880 --> 01:06:22,220
(What kind of dessert is Dessert Macho making?)

1331
01:06:22,380 --> 01:06:26,950
(Petite chocolate mousse)

1332
01:06:30,690 --> 01:06:34,060
(Ambroise)

1333
01:06:38,570 --> 01:06:39,570
(Clearing his throat)

1334
01:06:43,700 --> 01:06:45,670
I run a bakery...

1335
01:06:47,240 --> 01:06:50,740
in Asan, South Chungcheong Province. My name is Lee Kyung Mu.

1336
01:06:53,810 --> 01:06:55,620
My signature bread?

1337
01:06:57,120 --> 01:06:58,689
The raspberry gelee inside...

1338
01:06:58,690 --> 01:07:02,359
the chocolate mousse will give you the refreshing sour taste,

1339
01:07:02,360 --> 01:07:04,859
while the pistachio mousse will taste nutty.

1340
01:07:04,860 --> 01:07:07,189
There is also the rich taste of dark chocolate.

1341
01:07:07,190 --> 01:07:08,829
You will taste them in harmony.

1342
01:07:08,830 --> 01:07:13,830
(Pistachio mousse cream, pistachio sheet, raspberry gelee)

1343
01:07:14,270 --> 01:07:18,140
I wanted to create an interesting flavor combination.

1344
01:07:18,940 --> 01:07:20,310
I wonder if you will like it.

1345
01:07:23,740 --> 01:07:25,449
You are much shier...

1346
01:07:25,450 --> 01:07:26,579
than you look.

1347
01:07:26,580 --> 01:07:28,850
You're a macho guy,

1348
01:07:29,750 --> 01:07:32,020
but you are shy.

1349
01:07:32,450 --> 01:07:34,489
Don't they have a slang for that nowadays? Testo...

1350
01:07:34,490 --> 01:07:35,859
- Testo-man. - "Testo-man?"

1351
01:07:35,860 --> 01:07:36,860
- Te-estro-man. - Estro-man?

1352
01:07:36,920 --> 01:07:38,689
- He's both. - Yes.

1353
01:07:38,690 --> 01:07:40,089
He looks masculine outside,

1354
01:07:40,090 --> 01:07:41,260
- Right. Estro-man. - but is feminine inside.

1355
01:07:44,030 --> 01:07:46,000
- Shall we taste it? - Yes.

1356
01:07:46,030 --> 01:07:47,030
(Tasting Lee Kyung Mu's dessert)

1357
01:07:47,300 --> 01:07:51,400
(Will his delicate Ambroise show us a twist too?)

1358
01:07:52,470 --> 01:07:53,970
It's too pretty to cut.

1359
01:07:54,340 --> 01:07:56,309
- Do I have to eat this? - Yes.

1360
01:07:56,310 --> 01:07:58,880
- Do I have to eat this? - Isn't it too pretty?

1361
01:08:00,150 --> 01:08:01,850
It's a gift.

1362
01:08:02,220 --> 01:08:03,880
It's too pretty to eat.

1363
01:08:06,390 --> 01:08:08,250
- It's so soft. - It's really soft.

1364
01:08:11,930 --> 01:08:13,190
I see.

1365
01:08:17,330 --> 01:08:19,200
(Delicious!)

1366
01:08:22,540 --> 01:08:23,670
Gosh...

1367
01:08:27,610 --> 01:08:29,979
I was afraid of two judges the most.

1368
01:08:29,980 --> 01:08:32,080
Master Lee Seok Won and Chef Kim Narae.

1369
01:08:32,250 --> 01:08:34,409
I'm not about making things fancy.

1370
01:08:34,410 --> 01:08:36,679
I tend to focus more on classical tastes.

1371
01:08:36,680 --> 01:08:38,019
I knew I would have no hope...

1372
01:08:38,020 --> 01:08:39,450
if those two failed me.

1373
01:08:43,390 --> 01:08:47,030
I actually know...

1374
01:08:47,760 --> 01:08:48,860
Dessert Macho well.

1375
01:08:49,460 --> 01:08:52,170
I thought you were only good at making bread,

1376
01:08:52,770 --> 01:08:53,770
but my goodness...

1377
01:08:56,470 --> 01:08:57,840
Great texture.

1378
01:09:04,680 --> 01:09:05,879
But...

1379
01:09:05,880 --> 01:09:07,780
(But?)

1380
01:09:07,980 --> 01:09:09,849
The experts in the field...

1381
01:09:09,850 --> 01:09:12,750
must not be happy with the desserts these days.

1382
01:09:13,250 --> 01:09:14,250
Am I right?

1383
01:09:14,420 --> 01:09:15,420
Right.

1384
01:09:15,690 --> 01:09:17,589
That was exactly why...

1385
01:09:17,590 --> 01:09:20,290
I decided not to use a silicon mold for my mousse.

1386
01:09:21,060 --> 01:09:23,830
But I look at things from a commercial viewpoint.

1387
01:09:24,060 --> 01:09:26,070
For me, this is old-fashioned.

1388
01:09:26,430 --> 01:09:29,500
It doesn't have marketability.

1389
01:09:29,600 --> 01:09:33,539
Its look is not fitting for current trends.

1390
01:09:33,540 --> 01:09:34,970
It is too traditional.

1391
01:09:35,010 --> 01:09:36,339
It's old-fashioned.

1392
01:09:36,340 --> 01:09:39,680
It reminds me of the cakes from Japan in the 1990s.

1393
01:09:40,010 --> 01:09:41,080
It's the same style.

1394
01:09:42,380 --> 01:09:44,249
It felt like a wake-up call.

1395
01:09:44,250 --> 01:09:46,589
I only thought about the product.

1396
01:09:46,590 --> 01:09:49,259
It made me think that I should think further...

1397
01:09:49,260 --> 01:09:51,220
and prepare better.

1398
01:09:52,390 --> 01:09:55,160
It is now time to make a decision.

1399
01:10:01,400 --> 01:10:04,900
I'm also curious to find out what the result might be.

1400
01:10:06,240 --> 01:10:08,069
Did you all cast your votes?

1401
01:10:08,070 --> 01:10:09,080
Yes.

1402
01:10:11,110 --> 01:10:13,610
All right. Let's check the result.

1403
01:10:15,450 --> 01:10:16,650
I'm so curious.

1404
01:10:20,390 --> 01:10:22,820
(What is the result of Ambroise?)

1405
01:10:27,230 --> 01:10:28,999
(It wasn't trendy,)

1406
01:10:29,000 --> 01:10:32,400
(but it had its basics mastered.)

1407
01:10:36,940 --> 01:10:39,110
(Lee Kyung Mu passed.)

1408
01:10:43,040 --> 01:10:44,710
Yes. You passed.

1409
01:10:44,910 --> 01:10:47,750
Lee Kyung Mu, please continue to bake your dream.

1410
01:10:49,550 --> 01:10:51,920
(Lee Kyung Mu)

1411
01:10:52,320 --> 01:10:55,490
Amazing. What is this? It's crazy.

1412
01:10:56,160 --> 01:10:57,560
Everyone is passing.

1413
01:10:57,960 --> 01:10:59,030
Amazing.

1414
01:11:02,400 --> 01:11:04,430
There are too many competitors.

1415
01:11:05,800 --> 01:11:08,670
Narae, did you vote pass or fail?

1416
01:11:09,570 --> 01:11:10,899
I passed him.

1417
01:11:10,900 --> 01:11:14,570
He remained within the scope of the judging criteria.

1418
01:11:15,010 --> 01:11:17,209
But personally, it's not my taste.

1419
01:11:17,210 --> 01:11:18,380
Why is that?

1420
01:11:18,480 --> 01:11:21,309
I'm someone who makes it on a daily basis.

1421
01:11:21,310 --> 01:11:23,679
Right. It's your area of expertise.

1422
01:11:23,680 --> 01:11:24,750
You must have a higher standard.

1423
01:11:25,820 --> 01:11:29,590
(This contender is adding cream with a piping bag.)

1424
01:11:31,060 --> 01:11:32,730
This person is named Baking Teacher.

1425
01:11:32,790 --> 01:11:34,660
- Yes, Oh Se Sung. - Oh Se Sung.

1426
01:11:34,990 --> 01:11:36,060
He must be a teacher.

1427
01:11:37,330 --> 01:11:39,500
- But he looks really young. - Yes.

1428
01:11:39,830 --> 01:11:41,829
Hello. I'm the department head of baking...

1429
01:11:41,830 --> 01:11:43,599
at a cooking school.

1430
01:11:43,600 --> 01:11:45,910
I'm Baking Teacher, Oh Se Sung.

1431
01:11:46,470 --> 01:11:49,010
I mostly teach students who want to compete.

1432
01:11:50,180 --> 01:11:52,949
They won not only domestically but internationally as well.

1433
01:11:52,950 --> 01:11:55,750
They have won for three consecutive years.

1434
01:11:58,150 --> 01:12:00,490
Since my focus is on competitions,

1435
01:12:01,190 --> 01:12:04,860
plated desserts are my strength.

1436
01:12:07,660 --> 01:12:09,630
At every restaurant in France,

1437
01:12:10,100 --> 01:12:11,660
they have plated desserts.

1438
01:12:11,930 --> 01:12:15,769
But in Korea, we're not familiar with plated desserts.

1439
01:12:15,770 --> 01:12:16,870
Not really.

1440
01:12:18,340 --> 01:12:20,739
The dessert I made...

1441
01:12:20,740 --> 01:12:23,109
is Pistachio Apple Saint-Honore.

1442
01:12:23,110 --> 01:12:24,179
(A variation of a traditional French dessert...)

1443
01:12:24,180 --> 01:12:25,239
(with a creamy center and choux on top)

1444
01:12:25,240 --> 01:12:28,550
There is pistachio cream and apple ganache cream inside,

1445
01:12:29,020 --> 01:12:32,550
with some choux on top. It is such a dessert.

1446
01:12:36,420 --> 01:12:39,089
A student of mine tried it and loved it so much...

1447
01:12:39,090 --> 01:12:41,590
that they would eat this over a meal.

1448
01:12:42,900 --> 01:12:46,300
I chose the dessert my students liked the most.

1449
01:12:50,740 --> 01:12:54,610
(How will they like the dessert his students love?)

1450
01:12:59,350 --> 01:13:01,450
I have a feeling he will pass.

1451
01:13:01,980 --> 01:13:03,279
I think he'll pass.

1452
01:13:03,280 --> 01:13:04,880
Yes. He did a good job.

1453
01:13:06,490 --> 01:13:07,589
(Baking Teacher, Oh Se Sung)

1454
01:13:07,590 --> 01:13:09,920
Here comes the next bread.

1455
01:13:10,690 --> 01:13:11,919
Oh Se Sung.

1456
01:13:11,920 --> 01:13:13,159
Is this a Saint-Honore?

1457
01:13:13,160 --> 01:13:14,460
Yes, I think so.

1458
01:13:21,230 --> 01:13:22,600
Goodness. Apple dill?

1459
01:13:26,270 --> 01:13:30,340
(Master Kim Narae takes a cautious bite.)

1460
01:13:31,510 --> 01:13:33,150
I got nervous then.

1461
01:13:34,210 --> 01:13:35,310
When should I go in?

1462
01:13:36,520 --> 01:13:37,850
I was worried but excited.

1463
01:13:42,090 --> 01:13:45,420
(He's more nervous than ever in front of dessert masters.)

1464
01:13:52,670 --> 01:13:54,670
(Was his dessert returned?)

1465
01:13:58,400 --> 01:13:59,410
What?

1466
01:14:00,010 --> 01:14:01,240
- What is this? - What happened?

1467
01:14:01,810 --> 01:14:02,810
What?

1468
01:14:02,811 --> 01:14:04,880
(The conveyor belt moves in the opposite direction.)

1469
01:14:07,010 --> 01:14:11,450
(This has never happened before. The dessert has returned.)

1470
01:14:15,420 --> 01:14:17,460
Baking Teacher, Oh Se Sung.

1471
01:14:18,060 --> 01:14:19,060
You are eliminated.

1472
01:14:19,061 --> 01:14:20,530
(Baking Teacher, Oh Se Sung)

1473
01:14:20,730 --> 01:14:23,360
You are not allowed to enter the evaluation room.

1474
01:14:23,930 --> 01:14:26,530
Please leave the bread factory.

1475
01:14:28,170 --> 01:14:29,240
No way.

1476
01:14:29,970 --> 01:14:31,169
This is insane.

1477
01:14:31,170 --> 01:14:32,370
(Did he get terminated without an evaluation?)

1478
01:14:36,310 --> 01:14:37,310
What is this?

1479
01:14:40,910 --> 01:14:41,910
What is it?

1480
01:14:44,750 --> 01:14:48,050
(He was the first contender who couldn't get evaluated.)

1481
01:14:48,550 --> 01:14:49,890
This is so cruel.

1482
01:14:51,160 --> 01:14:52,690
It is. I wonder why.

1483
01:14:53,730 --> 01:14:57,500
Everyone was extremely stressed because of it.

1484
01:14:59,730 --> 01:15:02,570
(The reason why his dessert was sent back)

1485
01:15:03,300 --> 01:15:07,039
First off, the choux. The colors don't match.

1486
01:15:07,040 --> 01:15:08,909
This wasn't caramelized enough.

1487
01:15:08,910 --> 01:15:10,580
This one has a different color.

1488
01:15:11,080 --> 01:15:12,979
The cream's texture is wrong too.

1489
01:15:12,980 --> 01:15:15,050
So...

1490
01:15:16,750 --> 01:15:17,820
I will pass.

1491
01:15:19,250 --> 01:15:20,650
You don't have to taste it.

1492
01:15:26,230 --> 01:15:27,830
Nothing is in harmony.

1493
01:15:27,930 --> 01:15:28,930
Harmony?

1494
01:15:28,931 --> 01:15:30,600
Yes. The taste's composition.

1495
01:15:30,700 --> 01:15:31,700
I see.

1496
01:15:31,701 --> 01:15:34,199
They might be good on their own,

1497
01:15:34,200 --> 01:15:36,940
but when they come together, they clash.

1498
01:15:38,700 --> 01:15:40,809
(First round of evaluation)

1499
01:15:40,810 --> 01:15:43,710
(If all the masters agree, they can refuse to evaluate.)

1500
01:15:49,450 --> 01:15:53,490
I actually ran into many issues during the process.

1501
01:15:53,920 --> 01:15:57,190
It wasn't an oven I was used to.

1502
01:15:58,120 --> 01:15:59,990
It was completely different.

1503
01:16:01,390 --> 01:16:03,459
I could feel that it wasn't going well.

1504
01:16:03,460 --> 01:16:04,760
(He could not show his A-game.)

1505
01:16:05,030 --> 01:16:08,830
However, I still thought I would receive an evaluation.

1506
01:16:11,070 --> 01:16:12,839
I cannot help...

1507
01:16:12,840 --> 01:16:16,109
but be more strict with French baked goods.

1508
01:16:16,110 --> 01:16:18,440
It's where I work...

1509
01:16:18,740 --> 01:16:21,850
and what I make every day.

1510
01:16:22,310 --> 01:16:24,520
I'm more faint-hearted these days.

1511
01:16:25,850 --> 01:16:28,290
My heart is racing after seeing him fail.

1512
01:16:28,990 --> 01:16:31,420
The conveyor belt didn't take it in.

1513
01:16:32,120 --> 01:16:34,390
I was shocked to see him fail then and there.

1514
01:16:35,760 --> 01:16:39,230
I thought I could be next.

1515
01:16:42,330 --> 01:16:43,970
Will there be a place for me?

1516
01:16:45,040 --> 01:16:47,510
I only thought I should work harder.

1517
01:16:48,640 --> 01:16:50,810
I was surprised. I was shocked.

1518
01:16:51,240 --> 01:16:53,310
(Tension heightens in the room.)

1519
01:16:54,180 --> 01:16:56,279
(He is still waiting.)

1520
01:16:56,280 --> 01:16:57,780
Lim Dong Seok...

1521
01:16:58,150 --> 01:16:59,250
The button...

1522
01:16:59,850 --> 01:17:02,389
He's moving. He's finally moving.

1523
01:17:02,390 --> 01:17:03,790
Was he fermenting or baking?

1524
01:17:03,990 --> 01:17:05,160
I'm so curious.

1525
01:17:06,430 --> 01:17:07,789
- Fermenting. - Fermenting.

1526
01:17:07,790 --> 01:17:09,330
- Yes. - He's checking how much it rose.

1527
01:17:11,330 --> 01:17:15,770
(The dough has finished its second proofing.)

1528
01:17:17,300 --> 01:17:18,700
Should I try baking it?

1529
01:17:22,240 --> 01:17:25,510
(His bread is now in the oven.)

1530
01:17:26,080 --> 01:17:27,650
Lim Dong Seok is moving.

1531
01:17:29,050 --> 01:17:30,419
- He's baking. - It's in the oven.

1532
01:17:30,420 --> 01:17:31,479
It's in the oven.

1533
01:17:31,480 --> 01:17:33,190
- When did he put it in? - Finally.

1534
01:17:33,290 --> 01:17:34,290
He didn't move for the longest time.

1535
01:17:34,291 --> 01:17:35,719
But when he does, he's fast.

1536
01:17:35,720 --> 01:17:36,720
You're right.

1537
01:17:37,920 --> 01:17:41,290
(The bread is nearly ready after a waiting period.)

1538
01:17:42,090 --> 01:17:43,460
It's finally coming in.

1539
01:17:44,500 --> 01:17:45,529
Finally.

1540
01:17:45,530 --> 01:17:46,530
Finally.

1541
01:17:47,630 --> 01:17:49,899
- Chef Lim Dong Seok. - It looks really good.

1542
01:17:49,900 --> 01:17:51,800
(Contender Lim Dong Seok caught everyone's attention.)

1543
01:17:52,840 --> 01:17:55,370
(Master of Selling Out, Lim Dong Seok)

1544
01:17:55,640 --> 01:17:58,540
- We've all been waiting for this. - Yes, the bread is coming in.

1545
01:18:00,950 --> 01:18:02,149
Is that salt on the surface?

1546
01:18:02,150 --> 01:18:04,080
- Yes, it's salt. - It's salt ciabatta.

1547
01:18:05,220 --> 01:18:06,450
- It looks tasty. - It's like salt bread.

1548
01:18:06,890 --> 01:18:07,890
I'm excited.

1549
01:18:07,891 --> 01:18:09,050
(Salt ciabatta)

1550
01:18:14,130 --> 01:18:15,330
- Hello. - Hello!

1551
01:18:15,530 --> 01:18:16,560
- Hello. - Welcome.

1552
01:18:17,230 --> 01:18:18,399
Could you introduce yourself...

1553
01:18:18,400 --> 01:18:20,470
as well as your signature bread?

1554
01:18:20,800 --> 01:18:22,470
I run a bakery in Gocheok-dong, Guro-gu...

1555
01:18:22,740 --> 01:18:24,739
named Soo Mil Boulangerie.

1556
01:18:24,740 --> 01:18:26,270
My name is Lim Dong Seok.

1557
01:18:27,740 --> 01:18:31,780
(The queue is long, even before opening hours.)

1558
01:18:34,780 --> 01:18:37,020
- Welcome! - Good morning.

1559
01:18:37,320 --> 01:18:39,719
Many customers visit the bakery.

1560
01:18:39,720 --> 01:18:41,089
So we open at 10am,

1561
01:18:41,090 --> 01:18:44,090
and we're all sold out by the time it's 1pm to 2pm.

1562
01:18:46,590 --> 01:18:48,960
(On this day, he sold out in just 2 hours after opening.)

1563
01:18:51,000 --> 01:18:53,600
I make as much as I can every day,

1564
01:18:53,770 --> 01:18:54,999
but it all gets sold out.

1565
01:18:55,000 --> 01:18:57,400
I'm very grateful for all the love my bread receives.

1566
01:18:59,170 --> 01:19:03,180
The most popular bread is the salt ciabatta,

1567
01:19:03,610 --> 01:19:04,839
and that's why I chose it as my signature bread.

1568
01:19:04,840 --> 01:19:06,110
(Salt ciabatta)

1569
01:19:06,410 --> 01:19:08,650
I put butter in the dough,

1570
01:19:09,180 --> 01:19:11,350
which gives it a rich flavor.

1571
01:19:11,550 --> 01:19:14,450
It also makes the bread more moist and chewy,

1572
01:19:14,720 --> 01:19:15,990
making the taste harmonious.

1573
01:19:17,390 --> 01:19:21,030
(This is the secret behind his crunchy yet chewy ciabatta.)

1574
01:19:23,030 --> 01:19:24,460
It's really crispy on the outside,

1575
01:19:25,160 --> 01:19:26,630
and I think that's the strongpoint.

1576
01:19:29,540 --> 01:19:32,000
The bread I usually make isn't that showy,

1577
01:19:32,270 --> 01:19:35,270
and the only thing I can show for my bread is the taste itself.

1578
01:19:35,340 --> 01:19:39,480
That's the only thing I focused on.

1579
01:19:40,810 --> 01:19:43,379
Would my bread appeal to the Masters too?

1580
01:19:43,380 --> 01:19:44,780
(Will the salt ciabatta appeal to the Masters?)

1581
01:19:51,220 --> 01:19:52,489
It smells amazing.

1582
01:19:52,490 --> 01:19:53,630
It's really unique.

1583
01:19:57,730 --> 01:19:59,569
People don't usually use butter when making ciabatta.

1584
01:19:59,570 --> 01:20:01,970
That's right. Usually, olive oil is used.

1585
01:20:02,470 --> 01:20:04,439
I applied salt bread to make the ciabatta,

1586
01:20:04,440 --> 01:20:07,010
and added butter when moulding the dough.

1587
01:20:08,470 --> 01:20:11,079
For salt breads, this hole in the middle is crucial.

1588
01:20:11,080 --> 01:20:12,080
Yes, the open crumb.

1589
01:20:12,081 --> 01:20:14,380
- So that's what you were going for. - That's right.

1590
01:20:14,810 --> 01:20:16,849
The butter needs to melt down.

1591
01:20:16,850 --> 01:20:19,450
It needs to make a hole and melt down to the side...

1592
01:20:19,650 --> 01:20:21,120
to fry the crust.

1593
01:20:21,620 --> 01:20:25,190
That's how you make bread with a crispy crust.

1594
01:20:25,390 --> 01:20:26,430
Yes.

1595
01:20:28,330 --> 01:20:30,430
- When you were making the bread, - Yes.

1596
01:20:30,830 --> 01:20:33,029
you were just staring into the distance,

1597
01:20:33,030 --> 01:20:34,399
- deep in thought. - Yes.

1598
01:20:34,400 --> 01:20:36,140
What were you thinking about back then?

1599
01:20:37,640 --> 01:20:38,394
I was...

1600
01:20:39,470 --> 01:20:41,470
actually really flustered.

1601
01:20:42,370 --> 01:20:43,380
How so?

1602
01:20:44,010 --> 01:20:47,679
I expected a lot of others to do cold fermentation,

1603
01:20:47,680 --> 01:20:49,680
but I was the only one doing long fermentation.

1604
01:20:50,280 --> 01:20:53,150
That's why I was taken aback.

1605
01:20:54,250 --> 01:20:56,320
It must not seem that way,

1606
01:20:56,720 --> 01:20:59,790
but I was planning everything out in my head.

1607
01:21:00,190 --> 01:21:04,530
It doesn't always show, but baking itself...

1608
01:21:05,000 --> 01:21:07,400
requires a lot of the baker's care and attention.

1609
01:21:07,630 --> 01:21:10,170
The temperature, humidity, weather, timing, and so on.

1610
01:21:10,500 --> 01:21:15,310
So many factors need to be taken into account by the baker.

1611
01:21:16,010 --> 01:21:20,280
I think that's the most important characteristic of baking,

1612
01:21:20,580 --> 01:21:24,150
and I hoped the Masters would understand this.

1613
01:21:42,600 --> 01:21:43,970
I don't know if I should say this,

1614
01:21:48,240 --> 01:21:50,179
but this is the best bread I had today.

1615
01:21:50,180 --> 01:21:52,210
(This is the best bread I had today.)

1616
01:21:52,610 --> 01:21:54,249
- Gosh, really? - I should try more.

1617
01:21:54,250 --> 01:21:55,280
Thank you.

1618
01:21:55,850 --> 01:21:58,950
I thought the use of butter was very unique.

1619
01:22:00,490 --> 01:22:02,119
The crust is really good too.

1620
01:22:02,120 --> 01:22:03,359
- The crust. - Right.

1621
01:22:03,360 --> 01:22:04,460
- It's amazing. - It really is.

1622
01:22:04,720 --> 01:22:06,059
It's extremely good.

1623
01:22:06,060 --> 01:22:08,730
(The salt ciabatta surprised all the Masters.)

1624
01:22:09,260 --> 01:22:11,660
Tear off the crust and try it. It's so good.

1625
01:22:12,260 --> 01:22:13,930
I'd like to learn the recipe from you.

1626
01:22:14,800 --> 01:22:16,640
- It's that good, Master Lee? - I'm flattered.

1627
01:22:18,170 --> 01:22:19,609
(Master of Selling Out, Lim Dong Seok passed.)

1628
01:22:19,610 --> 01:22:21,539
- Of course he passes. - Congratulations!

1629
01:22:21,540 --> 01:22:22,909
Congratulations, you passed!

1630
01:22:22,910 --> 01:22:25,640
- Thank you very much. - Congratulations!

1631
01:22:26,510 --> 01:22:27,580
He left right away.

1632
01:22:28,080 --> 01:22:29,750
(Looking around)

1633
01:22:31,880 --> 01:22:33,189
The way he's looking left and right...

1634
01:22:33,190 --> 01:22:35,320
- It's okay, you can leave! - reminds me of Chef Choi Gang Rok.

1635
01:22:35,690 --> 01:22:37,220
- They are really similar! - Right?

1636
01:22:37,690 --> 01:22:39,729
Those types are the real geniuses.

1637
01:22:39,730 --> 01:22:40,759
That's true.

1638
01:22:40,760 --> 01:22:42,860
Did anyone fail him?

1639
01:22:43,060 --> 01:22:44,299
- It was unanimous. - Yes.

1640
01:22:44,300 --> 01:22:45,300
- Everyone passed him. - I'd...

1641
01:22:45,301 --> 01:22:46,400
like to take this home.

1642
01:22:47,030 --> 01:22:48,830
(Bake Your Dream)

1643
01:22:49,400 --> 01:22:51,870
The next contender's bread is coming in.

1644
01:22:52,700 --> 01:22:56,010
(The bread comes in with its very own song.)

1645
01:22:57,740 --> 01:22:59,680
It's coming in with music.

1646
01:23:01,650 --> 01:23:02,980
- It's like a music box. - Right.

1647
01:23:04,280 --> 01:23:06,150
- Is it a ballerina? - A ballerina.

1648
01:23:06,850 --> 01:23:08,489
- A ballerina! - It's spinning.

1649
01:23:08,490 --> 01:23:09,490
- How cute. - Yes.

1650
01:23:11,120 --> 01:23:13,030
That looks amazing.

1651
01:23:15,660 --> 01:23:17,030
It looks prettier under the spotlight.

1652
01:23:23,170 --> 01:23:26,270
(This contender sent a ballerina in for this cold competition.)

1653
01:23:28,240 --> 01:23:31,539
Hello. I work at the fine-dining restaurant, CHOI,

1654
01:23:31,540 --> 01:23:34,449
and I'm in charge of the first and last course.

1655
01:23:34,450 --> 01:23:36,549
I'm the head pastry chef, Hwang Ji Oh.

1656
01:23:36,550 --> 01:23:38,549
(Crazy Pastry Chef, Hwang Ji Oh)

1657
01:23:38,550 --> 01:23:41,890
(CHOI is famous for their unique dessert courses.)

1658
01:23:42,320 --> 01:23:44,820
I still remember my first interview with her.

1659
01:23:45,090 --> 01:23:47,430
The moment I saw her, I knew she was crazy too.

1660
01:23:47,930 --> 01:23:50,160
She's crazy talented.

1661
01:23:50,500 --> 01:23:52,400
Ji Oh has so much creativity.

1662
01:23:53,630 --> 01:23:56,030
It's amazing. She's a good baker too.

1663
01:23:56,670 --> 01:23:58,700
Her basic skills and talent are impeccable.

1664
01:23:59,270 --> 01:24:01,970
She should win this thing, in my opinion.

1665
01:24:02,980 --> 01:24:04,040
I'm serious.

1666
01:24:04,340 --> 01:24:07,310
(Chef Choi Hyun Seok vouches for Contender Hwang Ji Oh.)

1667
01:24:08,750 --> 01:24:11,880
(She's squeezing something out.)

1668
01:24:13,420 --> 01:24:15,950
(It's a red sauce this time.)

1669
01:24:16,120 --> 01:24:17,819
- What is that? - It looks like gochujang.

1670
01:24:17,820 --> 01:24:18,920
Gochujang? Really?

1671
01:24:19,490 --> 01:24:20,530
I may be wrong.

1672
01:24:21,190 --> 01:24:23,560
(But it looks like he's right.)

1673
01:24:24,460 --> 01:24:25,529
What?

1674
01:24:25,530 --> 01:24:27,700
Is she putting gochujang in the batter?

1675
01:24:28,330 --> 01:24:29,430
That's so strange.

1676
01:24:29,970 --> 01:24:32,369
This is the very first...

1677
01:24:32,370 --> 01:24:34,810
signature dish that I made in CHOI.

1678
01:24:35,010 --> 01:24:36,980
I used three Korean pastes and a sauce,

1679
01:24:37,180 --> 01:24:39,909
soy sauce, gochujang, and doenjang in this dessert.

1680
01:24:39,910 --> 01:24:41,610
The ingredients themselves are very unique.

1681
01:24:42,510 --> 01:24:44,249
She's using the three popular...

1682
01:24:44,250 --> 01:24:46,050
Korean pastes and sauce in her dessert.

1683
01:24:47,390 --> 01:24:50,059
When heated, soy sauce and gochujang...

1684
01:24:50,060 --> 01:24:51,560
get a lighter texture.

1685
01:24:51,920 --> 01:24:54,660
Then I made doenjang into a syrup with rich flavor...

1686
01:24:55,060 --> 01:24:56,729
and put all three together.

1687
01:24:56,730 --> 01:24:59,870
This dessert has a unique yet unexpectedly harmonious flavor.

1688
01:25:00,770 --> 01:25:02,469
I'm curious about the flavor,

1689
01:25:02,470 --> 01:25:03,840
but I'd also like to know how it smells.

1690
01:25:04,040 --> 01:25:06,310
Soy sauce, gochujang, and doenjang all in one dessert.

1691
01:25:08,240 --> 01:25:11,239
I chose this as my signature bread because it has unique ingredients...

1692
01:25:11,240 --> 01:25:14,310
made with unique methods, and I think that resembled me.

1693
01:25:18,680 --> 01:25:21,720
(Ballerina)

1694
01:25:21,850 --> 01:25:24,320
My signature bread is called Ballerina.

1695
01:25:24,690 --> 01:25:27,659
It was made with the three popular Korean pastes and sauce,

1696
01:25:27,660 --> 01:25:30,999
soy sauce, gochujang, and doenjang.

1697
01:25:31,000 --> 01:25:32,359
(Soy sauce caramel, doenjang syrup, and gochujang sable)

1698
01:25:32,360 --> 01:25:34,269
The main ingredient is the soy sauce,

1699
01:25:34,270 --> 01:25:35,629
and it gives a savory flavor.

1700
01:25:35,630 --> 01:25:37,870
If you have a spoonful,

1701
01:25:38,070 --> 01:25:39,610
the flavor will fill your entire mouth.

1702
01:25:40,170 --> 01:25:42,169
You can still get a hint of the other pastes.

1703
01:25:42,170 --> 01:25:44,440
All three flavors come together quite nicely.

1704
01:25:45,480 --> 01:25:49,250
And the ballerina on top is edible.

1705
01:25:49,550 --> 01:25:51,480
It has a minty flavor.

1706
01:25:51,680 --> 01:25:55,950
Think of it as a palette cleanser.

1707
01:25:57,790 --> 01:25:59,359
Is the ballerina really made out of xylitol?

1708
01:25:59,360 --> 01:26:00,559
Yes, this is xylitol.

1709
01:26:00,560 --> 01:26:01,790
- Are you sure? - Yes, you can eat it.

1710
01:26:02,630 --> 01:26:03,760
- Really? - Yes.

1711
01:26:04,000 --> 01:26:07,430
(They try the ballerina decoration first.)

1712
01:26:15,570 --> 01:26:20,210
(Master Kim Narae is more strict when it comes to desserts.)

1713
01:26:36,730 --> 01:26:38,329
(Did Contender Hwang Ji Oh's Ballerina...)

1714
01:26:38,330 --> 01:26:40,070
(capture the hearts of the Masters?)

1715
01:26:43,500 --> 01:26:44,670
I thought...

1716
01:26:45,140 --> 01:26:49,539
the three pastes weren't as strong as I expected,

1717
01:26:49,540 --> 01:26:51,580
but that's not to say that they're missing.

1718
01:26:51,640 --> 01:26:55,280
The flavors were gentle, but in a harmonious way.

1719
01:26:56,250 --> 01:26:57,320
I liked that about it.

1720
01:26:58,680 --> 01:27:03,190
And you molded xylitol to make this decoration.

1721
01:27:03,520 --> 01:27:06,059
It's easy to break such a thin and delicate design,

1722
01:27:06,060 --> 01:27:08,489
but you presented it well.

1723
01:27:08,490 --> 01:27:09,490
Thank you.

1724
01:27:10,560 --> 01:27:11,660
It's really good.

1725
01:27:12,360 --> 01:27:14,900
(Ballerina is being judged positively.)

1726
01:27:17,100 --> 01:27:20,370
I actually thought...

1727
01:27:20,670 --> 01:27:22,670
the pastes and sauce...

1728
01:27:23,280 --> 01:27:26,310
were used in the dessert, but that's where it ends.

1729
01:27:26,680 --> 01:27:28,480
I hardly tasted them.

1730
01:27:28,980 --> 01:27:34,750
You have to show what's so special about the ingredients you used.

1731
01:27:35,820 --> 01:27:37,289
When you use an ingredient,

1732
01:27:37,290 --> 01:27:40,590
people should know exactly what they're tasting.

1733
01:27:40,660 --> 01:27:43,029
But I thought this dessert was missing that,

1734
01:27:43,030 --> 01:27:44,230
and I was a little disappointed.

1735
01:27:46,030 --> 01:27:49,430
(It's hard to tell whether she will pass or not.)

1736
01:27:50,400 --> 01:27:52,799
Okay. Now,

1737
01:27:52,800 --> 01:27:55,409
we will see the results for Crazy Pastry Chef,

1738
01:27:55,410 --> 01:27:58,080
Contender Hwang Ji Oh.

1739
01:28:03,010 --> 01:28:06,990
Will Contender Hwang Ji Oh pass or fail?

1740
01:28:08,650 --> 01:28:09,990
I felt like throwing up.

1741
01:28:10,420 --> 01:28:12,120
I was just too nervous.

1742
01:28:14,390 --> 01:28:17,060
(The Masters are curious to see the result too.)

1743
01:28:25,170 --> 01:28:26,870
(Crazy Pastry Chef, Hwang Ji Oh passed.)

1744
01:28:30,010 --> 01:28:32,509
Contender Hwang Ji Oh passed.

1745
01:28:32,510 --> 01:28:33,780
- Thank you. - Congratulations.

1746
01:28:34,810 --> 01:28:35,910
(Pass)

1747
01:28:37,950 --> 01:28:38,980
My gosh.

1748
01:28:39,680 --> 01:28:41,619
Could you say a few words, please?

1749
01:28:41,620 --> 01:28:42,650
Yes.

1750
01:28:43,860 --> 01:28:46,960
I'm so overwhelmed and happy right now.

1751
01:28:47,660 --> 01:28:50,830
And thank you for your feedback. I know exactly what you mean by it.

1752
01:28:51,260 --> 01:28:54,329
I will reflect on myself and try to become better.

1753
01:28:54,330 --> 01:28:56,130
- Thank you so much. - Yes.

1754
01:28:56,300 --> 01:28:57,500
Great work.

1755
01:28:58,570 --> 01:29:00,209
You have a way with words.

1756
01:29:00,210 --> 01:29:01,409
Thank you.

1757
01:29:01,410 --> 01:29:03,440
Did Chef Choi Hyun Seok teach you?

1758
01:29:03,910 --> 01:29:05,309
No, he didn't.

1759
01:29:05,310 --> 01:29:06,310
Did he teach you this?

1760
01:29:06,910 --> 01:29:08,109
I can't sprinkle salt that well,

1761
01:29:08,110 --> 01:29:09,650
- but I can toss flour well. - Gosh.

1762
01:29:10,320 --> 01:29:11,349
That's nice.

1763
01:29:11,350 --> 01:29:12,350
(Stay tuned for her work with flour!)

1764
01:29:12,920 --> 01:29:14,720
I think he's boiling milk to make cream.

1765
01:29:15,690 --> 01:29:17,990
I think a lot of Korean bakers like to use cream.

1766
01:29:18,060 --> 01:29:19,930
- Right. - Everyone is using cream.

1767
01:29:19,990 --> 01:29:21,729
Isn't he the owner of Fuhaha Cream Bread?

1768
01:29:21,730 --> 01:29:24,130
- You're right! - That place is really famous.

1769
01:29:24,300 --> 01:29:26,629
I poured my heart and soul...

1770
01:29:26,630 --> 01:29:27,630
into his cream bread.

1771
01:29:28,500 --> 01:29:30,899
I'm Lim Hoon, The Yeonnam-dong Hit Cream Bread.

1772
01:29:30,900 --> 01:29:31,969
(The Yeonnam-dong Hit Cream Bread, Lim Hoon)

1773
01:29:31,970 --> 01:29:32,970
He's a legend.

1774
01:29:32,971 --> 01:29:34,769
That place is so popular!

1775
01:29:34,770 --> 01:29:36,840
It's really good. You have to try it.

1776
01:29:37,010 --> 01:29:38,809
It's been 12 years since I first opened,

1777
01:29:38,810 --> 01:29:41,850
and most of my customers still come for the cream bread.

1778
01:29:42,610 --> 01:29:45,220
I think every Korean celebrity visited at least once.

1779
01:29:45,720 --> 01:29:47,850
I can't even give names. There were too many.

1780
01:29:48,550 --> 01:29:52,019
- Have you tried their bread? - I'm actually a regular.

1781
01:29:52,020 --> 01:29:54,059
- It's really famous. - I tried every flavor.

1782
01:29:54,060 --> 01:29:58,160
(Their cream bread is round and filled to the brim with cream.)

1783
01:29:58,330 --> 01:30:00,170
(Mimi fell in love at first bite.)

1784
01:30:02,600 --> 01:30:03,770
What is he doing?

1785
01:30:04,340 --> 01:30:07,040
- I think he's filtering bittern. - Really?

1786
01:30:07,140 --> 01:30:08,270
What does that mean?

1787
01:30:08,740 --> 01:30:11,039
This type of method...

1788
01:30:11,040 --> 01:30:12,710
is called clarification.

1789
01:30:13,410 --> 01:30:15,080
People use it to make cocktails too.

1790
01:30:15,910 --> 01:30:18,779
It's a method of purifying a solution.

1791
01:30:18,780 --> 01:30:19,780
(Clarification purifies milk by making it clot as it meets acid.)

1792
01:30:19,781 --> 01:30:20,789
(This method makes the color clearer and gives it a lighter texture.)

1793
01:30:20,790 --> 01:30:23,319
Fuhaha Cream Bread gives the impression...

1794
01:30:23,320 --> 01:30:25,219
that they just bake things simply.

1795
01:30:25,220 --> 01:30:26,759
- I thought so too! - But this is really fascinating.

1796
01:30:26,760 --> 01:30:28,259
I had no idea this is how their bread was made.

1797
01:30:28,260 --> 01:30:30,060
He's like a scientist!

1798
01:30:30,160 --> 01:30:31,330
It's really cool.

1799
01:30:32,130 --> 01:30:34,570
This must be why their bread is so good.

1800
01:30:34,730 --> 01:30:36,299
(Contender Lim Hoon impresses the Masters with his prowess.)

1801
01:30:36,300 --> 01:30:37,440
I'm so excited.

1802
01:30:38,200 --> 01:30:39,570
I wonder how it's going.

1803
01:30:40,810 --> 01:30:41,970
It's so hot.

1804
01:30:42,510 --> 01:30:43,640
He must be hot.

1805
01:30:44,580 --> 01:30:47,149
He keeps checking his dough with a thermometer.

1806
01:30:47,150 --> 01:30:49,580
(Groaning)

1807
01:30:49,680 --> 01:30:51,080
It's fermenting already.

1808
01:30:52,850 --> 01:30:55,589
He doesn't look too happy. Is there something wrong?

1809
01:30:55,590 --> 01:30:57,860
- No, Baker Lim Hoon! - The temperature must be too high.

1810
01:30:59,930 --> 01:31:01,590
Goodness...

1811
01:31:02,860 --> 01:31:04,329
The temperature of the dough is very important.

1812
01:31:04,330 --> 01:31:05,629
He's not happy with it at all.

1813
01:31:05,630 --> 01:31:06,769
Is it too high right now?

1814
01:31:06,770 --> 01:31:08,000
(Contender Lim Hoon quickly uses ice water to handle this.)

1815
01:31:11,270 --> 01:31:13,239
Is there a reason why the temperature should be low?

1816
01:31:13,240 --> 01:31:15,870
If it's too high, he can't ferment the bread when he wants to.

1817
01:31:15,940 --> 01:31:17,910
He's trying to lower the temperature to get the timing right.

1818
01:31:19,710 --> 01:31:21,310
My gosh.

1819
01:31:21,450 --> 01:31:22,579
When I was kneading the dough,

1820
01:31:22,580 --> 01:31:25,620
the temperature rose way faster than I expected.

1821
01:31:25,950 --> 01:31:28,049
I was extremely stressed.

1822
01:31:28,050 --> 01:31:29,990
- You can do it! - He's really composed, though.

1823
01:31:31,260 --> 01:31:35,760
(He's keeping his cool, even while dealing with crisis.)

1824
01:31:39,060 --> 01:31:40,370
It's going down.

1825
01:31:41,130 --> 01:31:42,300
It's getting cooler.

1826
01:31:46,040 --> 01:31:47,270
Thank goodness.

1827
01:31:47,510 --> 01:31:49,809
Thank goodness. The temperature went down.

1828
01:31:49,810 --> 01:31:51,010
(He succeeded in reaching the temperature he wanted.)

1829
01:31:51,340 --> 01:31:52,979
That's experience, right there.

1830
01:31:52,980 --> 01:31:55,210
All those years of experience helped him fix the issue.

1831
01:31:58,680 --> 01:31:59,719
Great.

1832
01:31:59,720 --> 01:32:00,749
(The dough is back to health.)

1833
01:32:00,750 --> 01:32:01,820
It worked.

1834
01:32:04,690 --> 01:32:06,659
I think I struggled the most in the beginning.

1835
01:32:06,660 --> 01:32:09,930
And after that, I just kept telling myself that I can do this.

1836
01:32:11,660 --> 01:32:14,399
It's the cream bread that Mimi has been waiting for.

1837
01:32:14,400 --> 01:32:15,400
(She's been looking forward to judging the cream bread.)

1838
01:32:15,401 --> 01:32:16,499
- Fuhaha. - Fuhaha.

1839
01:32:16,500 --> 01:32:18,000
Did he bring his cream bread?

1840
01:32:18,140 --> 01:32:20,369
- He didn't - What's wrong?

1841
01:32:20,370 --> 01:32:21,410
I've never seen that one before.

1842
01:32:21,570 --> 01:32:22,869
(It's a long cream bread.)

1843
01:32:22,870 --> 01:32:24,079
- You've never seen this shape? - You didn't try it before?

1844
01:32:24,080 --> 01:32:25,080
- It's usually round, right? - Yes.

1845
01:32:25,081 --> 01:32:26,480
It's a round cream bread.

1846
01:32:26,640 --> 01:32:30,720
(This bread is shaped differently from the usual round cream bread.)

1847
01:32:31,180 --> 01:32:33,489
(The Boy's Cream Bread)

1848
01:32:33,490 --> 01:32:34,650
This cream bread...

1849
01:32:35,350 --> 01:32:36,989
is not the cream bread...

1850
01:32:36,990 --> 01:32:40,690
that I've made and sold for the last 12 years.

1851
01:32:41,190 --> 01:32:42,190
Exactly.

1852
01:32:42,730 --> 01:32:47,699
In the last 2 to 3 years, cream bread...

1853
01:32:47,700 --> 01:32:48,730
What's wrong with me?

1854
01:32:49,030 --> 01:32:50,040
I'm so sorry.

1855
01:32:50,340 --> 01:32:51,699
- He must have a story. - I don't know why I'm crying.

1856
01:32:51,700 --> 01:32:53,510
- Take your time. - Gosh.

1857
01:32:55,540 --> 01:32:56,979
(Contender Lim Hoon suddenly sheds tears.)

1858
01:32:56,980 --> 01:32:58,780
People tell me...

1859
01:32:59,240 --> 01:33:01,080
that I found my success with this cream bread,

1860
01:33:01,750 --> 01:33:03,420
and I was really happy. But...

1861
01:33:04,880 --> 01:33:06,720
I'm so grateful for this bread,

1862
01:33:10,090 --> 01:33:11,860
but I hate it at the same time.

1863
01:33:13,460 --> 01:33:15,130
I am very grateful, but...

1864
01:33:16,430 --> 01:33:17,899
- Forgive me. - It's okay.

1865
01:33:17,900 --> 01:33:19,359
- I understand what you mean. - It's fine.

1866
01:33:19,360 --> 01:33:21,070
I'm very grateful for this bread,

1867
01:33:22,100 --> 01:33:23,500
but it feels like shackles.

1868
01:33:25,470 --> 01:33:28,639
For this competition, I wanted to bring out the bread...

1869
01:33:28,640 --> 01:33:31,510
that I've always wanted to make in the past,

1870
01:33:31,840 --> 01:33:33,480
and prove that I can bake other breads.

1871
01:33:34,080 --> 01:33:35,250
- I see. - I wanted to prove that...

1872
01:33:35,610 --> 01:33:37,780
and say farewell to my cream bread.

1873
01:33:39,920 --> 01:33:42,920
I really didn't think that I'd cry today too.

1874
01:33:43,250 --> 01:33:45,190
Gosh, stop crying.

1875
01:33:45,320 --> 01:33:46,459
(Master Lee Seok Won understands more than anyone else.)

1876
01:33:46,460 --> 01:33:47,560
There's no need to cry.

1877
01:33:48,190 --> 01:33:49,360
There's no need to cry.

1878
01:33:51,630 --> 01:33:56,000
They used to call this Creamy Bread.

1879
01:33:56,230 --> 01:33:59,170
It was massive, but it only had a drop of cream.

1880
01:34:03,940 --> 01:34:06,280
That cream bread got me into baking too.

1881
01:34:12,250 --> 01:34:14,519
So this is the bread that captures your life,

1882
01:34:14,520 --> 01:34:15,819
but you elevated it.

1883
01:34:15,820 --> 01:34:17,160
Yes, that's right.

1884
01:34:18,020 --> 01:34:22,589
12 years ago, I made the cream bread that a boy would've only imagined.

1885
01:34:22,590 --> 01:34:23,860
But this cream bread...

1886
01:34:24,660 --> 01:34:27,369
is the type of bread that the same boy would love.

1887
01:34:27,370 --> 01:34:29,270
That's the bread I tried to make.

1888
01:34:30,000 --> 01:34:32,300
Shall we try the cream bread?

1889
01:34:38,610 --> 01:34:40,980
The texture is exactly the same.

1890
01:34:41,710 --> 01:34:45,049
I wanted to show 12 years of work in one bread.

1891
01:34:45,050 --> 01:34:48,550
I want them to be reminded of the bread they had as a kid,

1892
01:34:48,650 --> 01:34:50,090
but also think that it tastes even better.

1893
01:34:53,560 --> 01:34:56,290
(Master Kim Narae's expression is unreadable.)

1894
01:34:58,630 --> 01:35:00,869
I noticed that you changed the cream.

1895
01:35:00,870 --> 01:35:04,139
Instead of using buttercream,

1896
01:35:04,140 --> 01:35:06,469
you used dairy cream in this bread.

1897
01:35:06,470 --> 01:35:08,610
I think that's what made it better.

1898
01:35:09,070 --> 01:35:11,009
It made me think of all the breads...

1899
01:35:11,010 --> 01:35:12,779
that were popular back in the day.

1900
01:35:12,780 --> 01:35:15,949
I liked that it made me reminisce.

1901
01:35:15,950 --> 01:35:17,080
(It reminds the Masters of the bread they had when they were young.)

1902
01:35:17,620 --> 01:35:18,650
Yes.

1903
01:35:20,020 --> 01:35:23,319
The bread you usually make is soft,

1904
01:35:23,320 --> 01:35:25,120
but somehow crumbly at the same time.

1905
01:35:25,560 --> 01:35:28,460
And when it meets the cream, the texture changes entirely.

1906
01:35:28,960 --> 01:35:30,859
It also reminds me of the bread...

1907
01:35:30,860 --> 01:35:33,599
that I used to have as a kid,

1908
01:35:33,600 --> 01:35:35,399
but it's also elegant.

1909
01:35:35,400 --> 01:35:38,969
That's why I love your bread so much.

1910
01:35:38,970 --> 01:35:41,369
And so I was a little disappointed today,

1911
01:35:41,370 --> 01:35:43,140
but I still enjoyed it very much.

1912
01:35:43,640 --> 01:35:45,440
- Thank you. - Gosh.

1913
01:35:48,810 --> 01:35:51,750
Then we will start the vote.

1914
01:35:52,350 --> 01:35:54,450
Please press the button.

1915
01:35:56,520 --> 01:35:59,360
I've been making just cream bread for 12 years.

1916
01:35:59,420 --> 01:36:02,360
Today, I'd like to see what I got out of all those years.

1917
01:36:03,760 --> 01:36:06,400
(The Masters are more hesitant than ever to make a decision.)

1918
01:36:06,600 --> 01:36:08,900
Now we will see whether The Yeonnam-dong Hit Cream Bread,

1919
01:36:09,070 --> 01:36:12,500
Contender Lim Hoon passed or failed.

1920
01:36:13,070 --> 01:36:15,239
(Did his back-to-the-basics cream bread...)

1921
01:36:15,240 --> 01:36:17,280
Is it a pass or a fail?

1922
01:36:17,710 --> 01:36:19,209
Please show us the result.

1923
01:36:19,210 --> 01:36:20,250
(move the hearts of the Masters?)

1924
01:36:20,680 --> 01:36:22,450
Please show us the result.

1925
01:36:25,280 --> 01:36:27,620
(I want to say farewell to my cream bread.)

1926
01:36:29,650 --> 01:36:30,959
(A feast of flavor)

1927
01:36:30,960 --> 01:36:32,159
(Basil caviar)

1928
01:36:32,160 --> 01:36:33,889
(Salmon)

1929
01:36:33,890 --> 01:36:35,159
(Bean sprouts)

1930
01:36:35,160 --> 01:36:36,529
(Unimaginable ingredients...)

1931
01:36:36,530 --> 01:36:37,599
(Exclaiming)

1932
01:36:37,600 --> 01:36:39,059
(are baked in unexpected ways.)

1933
01:36:39,060 --> 01:36:40,730
(This is first-class.)

1934
01:36:41,070 --> 01:36:42,629
I really enjoyed the presentation,

1935
01:36:42,630 --> 01:36:43,739
but...

1936
01:36:43,740 --> 01:36:45,469
(But)

1937
01:36:45,470 --> 01:36:46,669
(Unlike with cooking,)

1938
01:36:46,670 --> 01:36:48,410
(you can't make adjustments later with baking.)

1939
01:36:48,910 --> 01:36:50,910
This isn't something you can fix. It's finished, just like that.

1940
01:36:51,880 --> 01:36:53,080
Something is wrong.

1941
01:36:53,510 --> 01:36:54,710
Is there something going on?

1942
01:36:54,950 --> 01:36:56,210
I was so nervous.

1943
01:36:56,950 --> 01:36:59,080
The bread was a bit too hard for me.

1944
01:36:59,280 --> 01:37:01,519
The seasoning, the balance... Everything is wrong.

1945
01:37:01,520 --> 01:37:02,789
It's a hard no for me.

1946
01:37:02,790 --> 01:37:04,920
(A single mistake...)

1947
01:37:05,760 --> 01:37:08,060
(can change everything.)

1948
01:37:08,290 --> 01:37:09,083
Please...

1949
01:37:11,860 --> 01:37:12,860
Come out.

1950
01:37:12,861 --> 01:37:16,070
(Bake Your Dream)
